[White "Why 1.e4?"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "01 1.e4 introduction"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4668631"]

1. e4 {Why 1.e4? At master level, 1.e4 is the most popular first move. White 
controls the center, opens the diagonal for his light-squared bishop (bringing 
himself one step closer to castling), and prepares to start developing. 1.e4 has 
been the favorite of many world champions and amateurs alike. One key aspect of 
1.e4 compared to other popular first moves such as 1.d4 is that the resulting 
positions tend to be a bit more open, and there are fewer transpositions to 
other openings.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "1.e4 e5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the Petroff"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 1.e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4668695"]

1. e4 e5 {1... e5 is the most classical way for Black to play, controlling the 
center and opening up lines for his pieces. Since Black is down a tempo in an 
otherwise symmetrical position, White will be able to fight for the initiative.} 
2. Nf3 {White develops his kingside knight and attacks the e5-pawn.} Nf6 3. Nxe5 
{2... Nf6, known as the Petroff Defense, is one of the most solid choices for 
Black. It was popularized by Kramnik as a drawing weapon, a reputation that it 
has maintained through the years. While at the super-GM level the Petroff might 
be considered drawish, at lower levels it can be quite fun to play as White 
because Black has very little counterplay and is usually focused on trying to 
limit White's advantage. White should not be afraid to snatch the e5-pawn since 
...Qe7 can always be met by d4.} d6 (3... Nxe4 $6 4. Qe2 Qe7 (4... Nf6 $4 5. 
Nc6+ {wins the Black queen}) 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 {White can either hang on to the 
pawn where Black has insufficient compensation or focus more on development and 
force Black to lose time winning the pawn back.}) 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 {White grabs 
his share of the center and prepares to start developing his pieces.} d5 (5... 
Be7 6. Bd3 Nf6 {would leave Black in an uncomfortable situation due to White's 
space advantage.}) 6. Bd3 {[%cal Be1g1,Bh1f1,Bf1e1,Bc2c4,Bd1c2,Bb1c3][%csl Re4] 
White develops his light-squared bishop in preparation for castling. White will 
soon apply pressure on the center (especially the e4-knight) with moves like c4, 
Nc3, Qc2, and Re1. For a model game in this variation, see *Judit Polgar vs. 
Anatoly Karpov*.} *

