[White "Introduction to the"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez (Berlin)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 1.e4 e5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4668699"]

1. e4 e5 {1... e5 is the most classical way for Black to play, controlling the 
center and opening up lines for his pieces. Since Black is down a tempo in an 
otherwise symmetrical position, White will be able to fight for the initiative.} 
2. Nf3 {White develops his kingside knight and attacks the e5-pawn.} Nc6 {Black 
develops his knight and defends the e5-pawn.} 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez. White 
increases the pressure on the e5-pawn and in many variations intends to play 
Bxc6 followed by Nxe5.} ({White isn't able to do this immediately, for example 
with} 3. Bb5 3... a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nxe5 $6 Qd4 $1 {where Black wins the pawn 
back with the initiative, but in many variations White will be able to take on 
e5 after preparation.}) {As a result of this pressure on the e5-pawn, Black 
generally plays ...a6 and ...b5 to release the pressure on the c6-knight. As a 
result, the middlegames in the 'Closed Spanish' can resemble the Italian Game, 
but White gets a better version because his bishop is more secure on b3 (...d5 
no longer comes with tempo) and because ...a6 and ...b5 gave White a hook (a4 
can open the queenside). Black has alternatives to this queenside expansion, but 
he always has to be aware of the possibility of White playing Bxc6 followed by 
Nxe5.} Nf6 4. O-O {The Berlin. Black develops his knight and attacks the 
e4-pawn. White castles in preparation for the opening of the e-file. If Black 
captures the e4-pawn, White would be able to win back the pawn at will with the 
Re1 skewer.} Nxe4 {The most popular and critical try.} (4... Bc5 5. c3 {followed 
by d4 gives White the initiative and transposes into the classical variation.}) 
(4... Be7 5. Re1 {with White's e4-pawn defended, White is now threatening Bxc6 
followed by Nxe5. Black is forced into playing} 5... d6 {, but after} 6. d4 
{White has superior center control.}) {White opens the e-file.} (Nxe4 5. Re1 {is 
also possible but generally leads to more drawish positions due to the 
symmetrical pawn structure.}) 5. d4 Nd6 {Black counterattacks the b5-bishop and 
removes his knight from the exposed e-file.} (5... exd4 6. Re1 d5 7. Nxd4 {White 
will win material with Nxc6 or f3. The only critical line is} 7... Bd6 {but 
after} 8. Nxc6 Bxh2+ 9. Kh1 $1 Qh4 10. Rxe4+ dxe4 11. Qd8+ Qxd8 12. Nxd8+ Kxd8 
13. Kxh2 {White has a better endgame due to his more active king and bishop 
pair.}) (5... Be7 6. Qe2 Nd6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. dxe5 {White has a space advantage 
and easier development.}) 6. Bxc6 {White exchanges to buy a tempo to take on e5 
and to double the Black pawns.} (6. dxe5 Nxb5 7. a4 {is also playable, but is 
more likely to lead to drawish positions due to the relatively symmetrical pawn 
structure.}) dxc6 {6... bxc6 makes no sense because it would inhibit Black's 
development.} 7. dxe5 {White regains the pawn and gains a tempo by attacking the 
d6-knight.} Nf5 {Black's knight steps aside. f5 is the best square for the 
knight because Black discourages White from keeping the queens on the board with 
e2 in view of ...d4.} (7... Ne4 8. Qe2 {White will centralize his pieces with 
the initiative. The e4-knight will have to move again, losing time.}) 8. Qxd8+ 
{[%cal Bb1c3,Bh2h3,Bg2g4,Bf1d1][%csl Gh2,Gg2,Gf2,Ge5] White enters an endgame in 
which Black has the bishop pair in exchange for his inferior pawn structure. 
White's plan is to create a passed pawn on the kingside using his pawn majority. 
If White is able to trade all of his pieces and create a kingside passed pawn, 
he will have a winning endgame.} *

