1. e4 e5 {1... e5 is the most classical way for Black to play, controlling the 
center and opening up lines for his pieces. Since Black is down a tempo in an 
otherwise symmetrical position, White will be able to fight for the initiative.} 
2. Nf3 {White develops his kingside knight and attacks the e5-pawn.} Nc6 {Black 
develops his knight and defends the e5-pawn.} 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez. White 
increases the pressure on the e5-pawn and in many variations intends to play 
Bxc6 followed by Nxe5.} ({White isn't able to do this immediately, for example 
with} 3. Bb5 3... a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nxe5 $6 Qd4 $1 {where Black wins the pawn 
back with the initiative, but in many variations White will be able to take on 
e5 after preparation.}) {As a result of this pressure on the e5-pawn, Black 
generally plays ...a6 and ...b5 to release the pressure on the c6-knight. As a 
result, the middlegames in the 'Closed Spanish' can resemble the Italian Game, 
but White gets a better version because his bishop is more secure on b3 (...d5 
no longer comes with tempo) and because ...a6 and ...b5 gave White a hook (a4 
can open the queenside). Black has alternatives to this queenside expansion, but 
he always has to be aware of the possibility of White playing Bxc6 followed by 
Nxe5.} f5 {The Schliemann gambit. Black's positional idea is to trade his f-pawn 
for White's center-pawn, giving him a central pawn majority. The tactical 
justification of 3... f5 is that 4. exf5?! gives Black excellent piece activity 
after 4... e4. The drawback of 3... f5 is Black provokes the opening of the 
position when he is behind on development.} 4. Nc3 {White prepares for the 
opening of the position by rapidly developing his pieces.} (4. exf5 $6 e4) (4. 
Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nxe5 $6 Qd4 $1 6. Qh5+ $2 g6 7. Nxg6 hxg6 {and Qd4 protects Rh8.}) 
(4. d3 {is a playable and solid alternative.}) fxe4 {The most critical move. 
White was threatening to take on f5 due to his control of the e4 square.} 5. 
Nxe4 d5 {Black provokes complications. 5... Nf6 is more solid. White sacrifices 
a piece, but will win material back soon by playing Nxc6.} 6. Nxe5 (6. Ng3 Bg4 
{allows Black to keep his pawn center}) dxe4 7. Nxc6 {Black's main 2 responses 
are 7... Qg5 and 7... Qd5 (counter-attacking rather than immediately 
recapturing) because bxc6 allows White to win at least the exchange and a pawn 
after 8. Bxc6+.} Qg5 {White is ahead a pawn, but his b5-bishop, c6-knight, and 
g2-pawn are all hanging. The alternatives are covered in more detail in the full 
1. e4 repertoire.} (7... bxc6 $2 8. Bxc6+ Bd7 9. Qh5+ $1 {forcing a concession 
before grabbing the exchange.} 9... Ke7 (9... g6 10. Qe5+ {with a fork}) 10. 
Qe5+ Be6 11. Bxa8 Qxa8 12. Qxc7+ {White is up material. Black has excellent 
piece activity which is good enough for partial compensation for his sacrificed 
material, but not full. White can safely finish his development with O-O and 
d3.}) (7... Qd5 $6 8. c4 Qd6 9. Nxa7+ Bd7 (9... c6 10. Nxc8+ Rxc8 11. Ba4) 10. 
Bxd7+ {White is up 2 pawns for no compensation and has ideas of Qh5+ (with Qe5) 
and Nb5 with O-O.}) 8. Qe2 Nf6 (8... Qxg2 $2 9. Qh5+ {gives White a decisive 
attack.}) 9. Nxa7+ (9. f4 Qxf4 10. Ne5+ c6 11. d4 Qh4+ 12. g3 Qh3 13. Bc4 Be6 
14. Bg5 {is a safe and relatively simple alternative that allows White to fight 
for a small advantage.}) Bd7 (9... Kd8 10. Nxc8) (9... c6 10. Nxc6) 10. Bxd7+ 
Nxd7 (10... Kxd7 11. Qb5+ {trades queens, consolidating White's material 
advantage.}) 11. f4 {White prevents ...Qxg2 and gains space.} Qc5 (11... Qxf4 $2 
12. d4 {followed by Nb5 and Rf1 gives White a powerful initiative.}) 12. Nb5 
Qxc2 (12... Be7 13. Nc3 {White will follow up with Qe3 and Black won't have 
enough compensation for the two sacrificed pawns.}) 13. d4 {Black does not have 
enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} (13. d4 13... Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2) (13. 
d4 13... Bb4+ 14. Kf2) *

