1. e4 e5 {1... e5 is the most classical way for Black to play, controlling the 
center and opening up lines for his pieces. Since Black is down a tempo in an 
otherwise symmetrical position, White will be able to fight for the initiative.} 
2. Nf3 {White develops his kingside knight and attacks the e5-pawn.} Nc6 {Black 
develops his knight and defends the e5-pawn.} 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez. White 
increases the pressure on the e5-pawn and in many variations intends to play 
Bxc6 followed by Nxe5.} ({White isn't able to do this immediately, for example 
with} 3. Bb5 3... a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nxe5 $6 Qd4 $1 {where Black wins the pawn 
back with the initiative, but in many variations White will be able to take on 
e5 after preparation.}) {As a result of this pressure on the e5-pawn, Black 
generally plays ...a6 and ...b5 to release the pressure on the c6-knight. As a 
result, the middlegames in the 'Closed Spanish' can resemble the Italian Game, 
but White gets a better version because his bishop is more secure on b3 (...d5 
no longer comes with tempo) and because ...a6 and ...b5 gave White a hook (a4 
can open the queenside). Black has alternatives to this queenside expansion, but 
he always has to be aware of the possibility of White playing Bxc6 followed by 
Nxe5.} a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O {White castles, inviting Black to take on e4 (known 
as the Open Spanish) . For Black, this is a critical juncture. He can go for 
Open Spanish lines with 5... Nxe4, or he can head for the Closed Spanish with 
5... Be7.} Nxe4 6. d4 {It is important to remember that in almost all cases, if 
Black takes on e4 before castling, White should try to open up the position with 
the central strike d4. As usual, 6. Re1 is playable but will lead to dryer 
positions due to the symetrical structure.} b5 {Black prepares to play ...d5.} 
({The immediate} 6... d5 {is suboptimal due to} 7. Nxe5 {.}) (6... exd4 {allows} 
7. Re1 d5 8. Nxd4 {winning material due to the double threat of Nxc6 and f3. The 
only critical line is} 8... Bd6 9. Nxc6 Bxh2+ 10. Kh1 $1 Qh4 11. Rxe4+ dxe4 12. 
Qd8+ Qxd8 13. Nxd8+ Kxd8 14. Kxh2 {but White is better due to his bishop pair 
and superior king activity.}) 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. Be3 {[%cal 
Bb1d2,Bc2c3,Bb3c2,Bf1e1][%csl Ge5,Re4] White prepares to play Nbd2 without 
blocking his dark-squared bishop. White has a space advantage plans to rapidly 
develop and challenge the e4-knight (c3, Nbd2, Re1). White also aims to force 
Black into a passive position by exchanging his e4-knight (giving White superior 
piece activity and a space advantage) or to trade all of the minor pieces except 
for Black's light-squared bishop and a White knight so that White will have a 
better minor piece (the Black light-squared bishop will be restricted). It's 
worth mentioning that if Black plays ...Nc5-xb3, cxb3 should be seriously 
considered in order to apply pressure down the open c-file against the weak 
c5-square and backward c7-pawn.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
