1. e4 e5 {1... e5 is the most classical way for Black to play, controlling the 
center and opening up lines for his pieces. Since Black is down a tempo in an 
otherwise symmetrical position, White will be able to fight for the initiative.} 
2. Nf3 {White develops his kingside knight and attacks the e5-pawn.} Nc6 {Black 
develops his knight and defends the e5-pawn.} 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez. White 
increases the pressure on the e5-pawn and in many variations intends to play 
Bxc6 followed by Nxe5.} ({White isn't able to do this immediately, for example 
with} 3. Bb5 3... a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nxe5 $6 Qd4 $1 {where Black wins the pawn 
back with the initiative, but in many variations White will be able to take on 
e5 after preparation.}) {As a result of this pressure on the e5-pawn, Black 
generally plays ...a6 and ...b5 to release the pressure on the c6-knight. As a 
result, the middlegames in the 'Closed Spanish' can resemble the Italian Game, 
but White gets a better version because his bishop is more secure on b3 (...d5 
no longer comes with tempo) and because ...a6 and ...b5 gave White a hook (a4 
can open the queenside). Black has alternatives to this queenside expansion, but 
he always has to be aware of the possibility of White playing Bxc6 followed by 
Nxe5.} a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O {White castles, inviting Black to take on e4 (known 
as the Open Spanish). For Black, this is a critical juncture. He can go for Open 
Spanish lines with 5... Nxe4, or he can head for the Closed Spanish with 5... 
Be7.} Be7 {The Closed Spanish is the most popular way for Black to play because 
it is quite difficult to survive in the sharp, open positions that arise after 
5...Nxe4 6. d4. Note that by blocking the e-file, Black actually threatens to 
take on e4 and win a pawn.} 6. Re1 {White protects his e4-pawn with his rook 
because he does not want to obstruct his long-term plan of c2-c3 followed by 
d2-d4. For example, 6. Nc3 would block the c3-square while 6. d3 would be slow 
(although it is still a perfectly viable option if White seeks a slow game).} b5 
{Black kicks back White's bishop to facilitate further development.} ({A 
careless move such as} 6... O-O {would allow} 7. Bxc6 {followed by} 8. Nxe5 {, 
winning a pawn.}) 7. Bb3 O-O {Castling at this moment is a very interesting 
option which is played quite a bit at the top level. The idea is to meet the 
usual 8. c3 with 8... d5!, giving up a pawn for the initiative. That line, which 
has garnered tremendous theoretical respect, is known as the Marshall Attack.} 
8. h3 {It is a good idea to avoid the Marshall with the quiet move h2-h3. White 
delays c3 in order to wait for Black to make a commitment. 8... d5 is not as 
strong because White still has the c3 square available for his knight in case 
the position opens up. White can afford to delay c3 because Black is not yet 
threatening to win the bishop pair with ...Na5 because his e5-pawn isn't yet 
supported by ...d6.} (8. c3 d5 $1 {is the Marshall gambit. Allowing the Marshall 
gambit would be extremely dangerous for the unprepared player, so it is safer 
(and likely just as theoretically sound) to avoid it with} 8. h3 {.}) (8. a4 {is 
another way of avoiding the Marshall.}) Bb7 (8... d6 9. c3 {transposes into the 
Closed Spanish.}) 9. d3 {White blunts the b7-bishop and prepares to develop his 
queenside.} d6 10. a3 {[%cal Bb1c3,Bc1g5,Bc3d5,Gc3e2,Ge2g3,Gd3d4][%csl Rb7,Re7]} 
(10. c3 {is also strong.}) {White prepares to meet ...Na5 with Ba2, preserving 
his bishop pair. White can fight for the advantage in this relatively symetrical 
position due to Black's passive bishops as the White bishops are less restricted 
by the pawn structure.} *

