1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann Defense is one of the most solid ways for Black to play 
against 1. e4. He plans to strike against White's center next with ...d5.} 2. d4 
{White takes the chance to occupy the center with pawns.} d5 3. e5 {White gains 
space in the center. This is known as the Advance Variation and is the most 
ambitious way of playing against the Caro-Kann. The Advance Variation is 
stronger in the Caro-Kann than in the French because if Black challenges White's 
center with ...c5, he will have to lose a tempo because he already played 
...c6.} c5 {Black challenges White's center.} 4. dxc5 {White captures Black's 
hanging pawn.} e6 {Black aims to recapture his c5-pawn.} 5. a3 {White prepares 
to support the e5-pawn with Bb2 after gaining space with b4.} Nc6 ({Capturing 
White's c5-pawn with} 5... Bxc5 {is likely to transpose after} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. b4 
{, though White would have the additional option of meeting ...Bxc5 with Qg4 due 
to the delay of Nf3.}) 6. Nf3 ({It's worth mentioning that the} 6. b4 {move 
order is less accurate due to} 6... a5 $1) Bxc5 {Now that ...Bg4 is impossible, 
it makes sense to protect White's e5-pawn.} 7. b4 Bb6 {White gains a tempo and 
prepares to play Bb2.} 8. Bb2 {[%cal Bf1d3,Be1g1,Bh1f1,Bf1e1,Bb1d2,Bc2c4][%csl 
Ge5,Rc8] White is overprotecting his e5-pawn as prophylaxis against the ...f6 
break and has a space advantage. White will finish his development with (Bd3, 
O-O, Re1, Nbd2) and can open the position with c4. Black has a rather passive 
position because of his blocked in light-squared bishop and space disadvantage. 
For a model game in this variation, see *Ian Nepomniachtchi vs. Dmitry 
Andreikin*.} *

