1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann Defense is one of the most solid ways for Black to play 
against 1. e4. He plans to strike against White's center next with ...d5.} 2. d4 
{White takes the chance to occupy the center with pawns.} d5 3. e5 {White gains 
space in the center. This is known as the Advance Variation and is the most 
ambitious way of playing against the Caro-Kann. The Advance Variation is 
stronger in the Caro-Kann than in the French because if Black challenges White's 
center with ...c5, he will have to lose a tempo because he already played 
...c6.} c5 {Black challenges White's center.} 4. dxc5 {White captures Black's 
hanging pawn.} Nc6 {The main line, counter-attacking White's e5-pawn. 
Unfortunately for Black, 4... Nc6 is refuted and 4... e6 should be preferred.} 
5. f4 $1 {White protects the e5-pawn. If Black wishes to win the pawn back he 
will have to play ...e6 followed by ...Bxc5.} e6 {Black prepares to recapture 
the c5-pawn with ...Bxc5.} 6. Be3 {The key idea. To win the sacrificed pawn 
back, Black will have to play ...d4, which is a major positional concession due 
to the weakened e4-square. White will be able to use the e4-square for his 
knight. Combined with ideas like Bd3 Qf3 and O-O-O, White will be able to fight 
for a powerful initiative and Black will not have compensation.} d4 7. Bf2 Bxc5 
8. Nd2 {[%cal Ba2a3,Bd2e4,Bd1f3,Bf1d3,Be1c1,Ba1d1][%csl Ge4,Rc5] White will have 
a powerful initiative due to his smooth development (Ne4, Qf3 or Qd2, Bd3, 
O-O-O), space advantage, and control of the e4-square. It's worth mentioning 
that White will likely play a3 before playing Ne4 in order to prevent ...Bb4+ 
(a3 is also useful so that Bd3 can't be met by ...Nb4-xd3).} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Caro-Kann"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the Caro-Kann:"]
[Black "3.e5 Bf5 4.h4 h6 5.g4 Be4"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Caro-Kann"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4671749"]

1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann Defense is one of the most solid ways for Black to play 
against 1. e4. He plans to strike against White's center next with ...d5.} 2. d4 
{White takes the chance to occupy the center with pawns.} d5 3. e5 {White gains 
space in the center. This is known as the Advance Variation and is the most 
ambitious way of playing against the Caro-Kann. The Advance Variation is 
stronger in the Caro-Kann than in the French because if Black challenges White's 
center with ...c5, he will have to lose a tempo because he already played 
...c6.} Bf5 {Black develops his light-squared bishop outside of his pawn chain 
in preparation for ...e6.} 4. h4 {“'The refutation of the Caro-Kann.' - 
Mikhail Tal (World Champion 1960-1961)” White seizes kingside space and 
prevents ...e6 for the time being due to g4 followed by h5 (...Be4 can be met 
with f3), trapping Black's bishop. This is one of the dynamic attempts to prove 
that the strategic idea behind the Caro-Kann is unsound. White's claim is that 
the f5-bishop is a target. Black's claim is that the activity is worth the 
concession of delaying ...c5 (when ...c5 comes, Black will have lost a tempo).} 
h6 {Black gives his light-squared bishop a retreat square on h7.} 5. g4 {White 
gains space with tempo.} Be4 {Black provokes f3. 5... Bh7 allows the same pawn 
sacrifice where White has the extra option of playing Nf3 before f4.} (5... Bd7 
{is more solid because White isn't able to play the e6 sacrifice.}) 6. f3 Bh7 7. 
e6 {[%cal Bf1d3,Bc1f4][%csl Rf8] White sacrifices a pawn to gain the e5-square 
and block in Bf8. Black will either accept the pawn or allow exf7+, preventing 
Black from castling. Either way, the light-squares around the king are weakened. 
If Black accepts the pawn sacrifice, White can control the e5-square with Bf4, 
followed by exploiting the light square weakness, starting with trading off the 
light squared bishop by playing Bd3. Either way, White has the initiative. For a 
model game in this variation, see *Maxime Vachier-Lagrave vs. Ding Liren*.} *

