1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann Defense is one of the most solid ways for Black to play 
against 1. e4. He plans to strike against White's center next with ...d5.} 2. d4 
{White takes the chance to occupy the center with pawns.} d5 3. e5 {White gains 
space in the center. This is known as the Advance Variation and is the most 
ambitious way of playing against the Caro-Kann. The Advance Variation is 
stronger in the Caro-Kann than in the French because if Black challenges White's 
center with ...c5, he will have to lose a tempo because he already played 
...c6.} Bf5 {Black develops his light-squared bishop outside of his pawn chain 
in preparation for ...e6.} 4. h4 {“'The refutation of the Caro-Kann.' - 
Mikhail Tal (World Champion 1960-1961)” White seizes kingside space and 
prevents ...e6 for the time being due to g4 followed by h5 (...Be4 can be met 
with f3), trapping Black's bishop. This is one of the dynamic attempts to prove 
that the strategic idea behind the Caro-Kann is unsound. White's claim is that 
the f5-bishop is a target. Black's claim is that the activity is worth the 
concession of delaying ...c5 (when ...c5 comes, Black will have lost a tempo).} 
h6 {Black gives his light-squared bishop a retreat square on h7.} 5. g4 {White 
gains space with tempo.} Bd7 {Black prevents the e6-sacrifice, but concedes 
White a kingside space advantage. After Black plays ...e6, his light-squared 
bishop will be very passive.} 6. Nc3 {[%cal 
Bc1e3,Bd1d2,Be1c1,Ba1d1,Bf2f4,Bh4h5][%csl Ge5,Gg4,Gh4,Gd4,Rd7] White resumes 
development. The burden of proof is on Black to prove that he can obtain 
compensation for White's easy development and space advantage.} (6. h5 {is 
structurally ideal, but Black is able to get concrete counterplay with} 6... c5 
$1 7. dxc5 Qc7 {. White should play Nc3 first because ...c5 would loosen up the 
d5-pawn too much.}) *

