1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann Defense is one of the most solid ways for Black to play 
against 1. e4. He plans to strike against White's center next with ...d5.} 2. d4 
{White takes the chance to occupy the center with pawns.} d5 3. e5 {White gains 
space in the center. This is known as the Advance Variation and is the most 
ambitious way of playing against the Caro-Kann. The Advance Variation is 
stronger in the Caro-Kann than in the French because if Black challenges White's 
center with ...c5, he will have to lose a tempo because he already played 
...c6.} Bf5 {Black develops his light-squared bishop outside of his pawn chain 
in preparation for ...e6.} 4. h4 {“'The refutation of the Caro-Kann.' - 
Mikhail Tal (World Champion 1960-1961)” White seizes kingside space and 
prevents ...e6 for the time being due to g4 followed by h5 (...Be4 can be met 
with f3), trapping Black's bishop. This is one of the dynamic attempts to prove 
that the strategic idea behind the Caro-Kann is unsound. White's claim is that 
the f5-bishop is a target. Black's claim is that the activity is worth the 
concession of delaying ...c5 (when ...c5 comes, Black will have lost a tempo).} 
h5 {Black prevents White from playing g4 at the cost of weakening the 
dark-squares (specifically g5). If Black didn't play ...h5 or ...h6, he wouldn't 
be able to develop his kingside (...e6 would always be met with g4).} 5. Bd3 
{White trades light-squared bishops in order to speed up his development. In 
this pawn structure without the inclusion of h4 and ...h5, White's remaining 
dark-squared bishop would usually be passive, but since Black played ...h5, 
White has the g5-square available.} Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 (6... Qa5+ {is well met by} 
7. Nd2 ({or} 7. Bd2 Qa6 8. e6 $1) 7... Qa6 8. c4 {with a space advantage.}) 7. 
Bg5 {White has a space advantage and a lead in development. Black is the one who 
has to prove that he can equalize and if he doesn't manage to favorably change 
the pawn structure, White will consolidate his advantage.} Be7 8. Nf3 {[%cal 
Bb1c3,Bc3e2,Be2g3,Be1g1,Bh1f1][%csl Ge5] Black has no way to fight for the 
initiative and is purely focused on limiting White's advantage. White plans to 
maneuver his queenside knight to g3 (Nc3-e2-g3) which is a useful way of 
combating ...Nh6-f5 (...Nxg3 is welcomed because it opens the f-file and Nxf5 is 
favorable because Black would obtain doubled pawns without compensation) and 
gain space on the queenside (b3 and c4) or fight for a kingside initiative.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Caro-Kann"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the Caro-Kann:"]
[Black "3.e5 Bf5 4.h4 h5 with 7...Qa5+"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Caro-Kann"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4671752"]

1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann Defense is one of the most solid ways for Black to play 
against 1. e4. He plans to strike against White's center next with ...d5.} 2. d4 
{White takes the chance to occupy the center with pawns.} d5 3. e5 {White gains 
space in the center. This is known as the Advance Variation and is the most 
ambitious way of playing against the Caro-Kann. The Advance Variation is 
stronger in the Caro-Kann than in the French because if Black challenges White's 
center with ...c5, he will have to lose a tempo because he already played 
...c6.} Bf5 {Black develops his light-squared bishop outside of his pawn chain 
in preparation for ...e6.} 4. h4 {“'The refutation of the Caro-Kann.' - 
Mikhail Tal (World Champion 1960-1961)” White seizes kingside space and 
prevents ...e6 for the time being due to g4 followed by h5 (...Be4 can be met 
with f3), trapping Black's bishop. This is one of the dynamic attempts to prove 
that the strategic idea behind the Caro-Kann is unsound. White's claim is that 
the f5-bishop is a target. Black's claim is that the activity is worth the 
concession of delaying ...c5 (when ...c5 comes, Black will have lost a tempo).} 
h5 {Black prevents White from playing g4 at the cost of weakening the 
dark-squares (specifically g5). If Black didn't play ...h5 or ...h6, he wouldn't 
be able to develop his kingside (...e6 would always be met with g4).} 5. Bd3 
{White trades light-squared bishops in order to speed up his development. In 
this pawn structure without the inclusion of h4 and ...h5, White's remaining 
dark-squared bishop would usually be passive, but since Black played ...h5, 
White has the g5-square available.} Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 {White has a space 
advantage and a lead in development. Black is the one who has to prove that he 
can equalize and if he doesn't manage to favorably change the pawn structure, 
White will consolidate his advantage.} Qa5+ 8. Nd2 Qa6 9. c4 {[%cal 
Bg1e2,Be2g3,Bb2b3,Be1g1,Bh1f1][%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge5] Black has no compensation for 
White's space advantage and lead in development. Note that this variation can 
also be reached via the 7... Qb6 8. Nd2 Qa6 move order.} *

