[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4671756"]

1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann Defense is one of the most solid ways for Black to play 
against 1. e4. He plans to strike against White's center next with ...d5.} 2. d4 
{White takes the chance to occupy the center with pawns.} d5 3. e5 {White gains 
space in the center. This is known as the Advance Variation and is the most 
ambitious way of playing against the Caro-Kann. The Advance Variation is 
stronger in the Caro-Kann than in the French because if Black challenges White's 
center with ...c5, he will have to lose a tempo because he already played 
...c6.} Bf5 {Black develops his light-squared bishop outside of his pawn chain 
in preparation for ...e6.} 4. h4 {“'The refutation of the Caro-Kann.' - 
Mikhail Tal (World Champion 1960-1961)” White seizes kingside space and 
prevents ...e6 for the time being due to g4 followed by h5 (...Be4 can be met 
with f3), trapping Black's bishop. This is one of the dynamic attempts to prove 
that the strategic idea behind the Caro-Kann is unsound. White's claim is that 
the f5-bishop is a target. Black's claim is that the activity is worth the 
concession of delaying ...c5 (when ...c5 comes, Black will have lost a tempo).} 
h5 {Black prevents White from playing g4 at the cost of weakening the 
dark-squares (specifically g5) . If Black didn't play ...h5 or ...h6, he 
wouldn't be able to develop his kingside (...e6 would always be met with g4).} 
5. Bd3 {White trades light-squared bishops in order to speed up his development. 
In this pawn structure without the inclusion of h4 and ...h5, White's remaining 
dark-squared bishop would usually be passive, but since Black played ...h5, 
White has the g5-square available.} Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 {White has a space 
advantage and a lead in development. Black is the one who has to prove that he 
can equalize and if he doesn't manage to favorably change the pawn structure, 
White will consolidate his advantage.} Qb6 {The most critical move. Black aims 
to take the b2-pawn in order to obtain compensation for White's space 
advantage.} 8. Nd2 c5 {Black's best chance to obtain counterplay is to 
counterattack White's center. Black has other options, but if Black just makes 
normal developing moves, he is likely to slip into a passive position.} (8... 
Ne7 9. Ngf3) (8... Qa6 9. c4) (8... Qxb2 9. Rb1) 9. c4 {White increases the 
tension in the center to prepare for the opening of the position. White prefers 
the position to be open rather than closed because with more open lines he would 
be able to use his lead in development to fight for a bigger initiative than he 
would have been able to in a closed game.} Qxb2 10. Rd1 $1 {White develops his 
rook and neutralizes ...Qxd4 (which can now be met by Qb3 where White's rook 
would be on a central file which has been opened) . The analysis which follows 
has mostly not occurred in rated master games yet as Rd1 is a relatively new 
idea (Rb1 was previously the most popular move) . While the position is very 
sharp, the position is harder for Black to play (and is more forcing for Black) 
because he only has his queen developed while White is able to rapidly develop 
everything. The central pawn tension makes matters worse for Black, as White is 
able to open the center at any time.} Nc6 {Black develops a piece and increases 
the pressure on White's center. “'The only move which gives Black real chances 
to defend against White's initiative, although he still needs to find some 
accurate moves to do so.' - GM John Shaw”} 11. Ngf3 {[%cal 
Be1g1,Bh1f1,Bd1b1,Bc4d5,Ge6d5,Ge5e6][%csl Re8,Rb2,Rb7,Rd5] White develops his 
knight and prepares to castle kingside. This is covered in more detail in the 
full course. “'This variation is interesting and not unlike a tightrope for 
Black to walk. I would hate defending Black's position, having to make many 
'only moves' just to make a draw.' - GM John Shaw”} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "French"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the French:"]
[Black "Steinitz with 7...cxd4"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4684451"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} Nf6 4. e5 {3... Nf6 is the Steinitz Variation. Black 
hits the e4-pawn, provoking White to advance. White gains space.} Nfd7 5. f4 
{White gains space and adds further support to the e5 pawn before playing Nf3.} 
c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 {White continues to support the d4-pawn. White has a space 
advantage, but Black has pressure on the center. Black's c-pawn is likely to be 
traded for White's d-pawn, which would give Black a central pawn majority but 
would give White an outpost on d4 for his knight.} cxd4 8. Nxd4 {[%cal 
Bd1d2,Be1c1,Ba1d1][%csl Gd4,Rc8] White will castle queenside and fight for a 
kingside initiative.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "French"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the French:"]
[Black "Steinitz with 7...Be7"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4684452"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} Nf6 4. e5 {3... Nf6 is the Steinitz Variation. Black 
hits the e4-pawn, provoking White to advance. White gains space.} Nfd7 5. f4 
{White gains space and adds further support to the e5 pawn before playing Nf3.} 
c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 {White continues to support the d4-pawn. White has a space 
advantage, but Black has pressure on the center. Black's c-pawn is likely to be 
traded for White's d-pawn, which would give Black a central pawn majority but 
would give White an outpost on d4 for his knight.} Be7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. dxc5 Bxc5 
{White should remember to make this exchange before castling queenside because 
...c4 followed by a queenside pawn storm would give Black a decisive attack 
otherwise. If Black committed to ...c4 before White castled long, White could 
castle kingside instead followed by a kingside pawn storm (f5 is easier to 
achieve if Black is not applying pressure on the d4-pawn).} 10. O-O-O {[%cal 
Bc1b1,Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Bd2f2,Bf1d3][%csl Gd4,Rc8] White will fight for a kingside 
initiative. It's worth mentioning that White is open to the exchange of 
dark-squared bishops because he has the better of the light-squared bishops. 
White is generally better in the endgame, especially an endgame where Black has 
a light-squared bishop against White's outposted d4-knight.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "French"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the French:"]
[Black "Steinitz with 7...a6"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4684453"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} Nf6 4. e5 {3... Nf6 is the Steinitz Variation. Black 
hits the e4-pawn, provoking White to advance. White gains space.} Nfd7 5. f4 
{White gains space and adds further support to the e5 pawn before playing Nf3.} 
c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 {White continues to support the d4-pawn. White has a space 
advantage, but Black has pressure on the center. Black's c-pawn is likely to be 
traded for White's d-pawn, which would give Black a central pawn majority but 
would give White an outpost on d4 for his knight.} a6 8. Qd2 b5 {Black prepares 
to play ...b5.} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 {White prepares to castle queenside by preventing 
...c4. Another benefit of dxc5 is that White now has the d4-square available for 
his knight.} 10. Bd3 {White develops and prepares to castle queenside. While 
White is open to the trade of dark-squared bishops, he would rather Black 
exchange on e3 (or f2 after Bf2) instead of White playing Bxc5 because Bxc5 
helps Black improve the activity of his d7-knight. The drawback of 10. Bd3 is 
that Black can 'win a piece' with 10... d4. If the complications after 10... d4 
favor White, then he gets a better version of the mainline 10. Bxc5 because he 
didn't help Black develop his knight. Unfortunately for Black, the complications 
after 10... d4 favor White.} (10. Bxc5 Nxc5 11. Bd3 {followed by Qf2 and O-O is 
a safe alternative to the complicated 10.Bd3.}) ({White doesn't play} 10. O-O-O 
{because Black has already started his pawn storm.}) Qb6 11. Bf2 {[%cal 
Be1g1,Bh1f1][%csl Rc8,Gd4] White keeps the tension and prepares to castle 
kingside. White has a lead in development, giving him good chances in the 
resulting middlegame. White would also have good chances in an endgame (for 
example if Black exchanged twice on f2) because of White's d4-outpost + space 
advantage and Black's weak dark-squares and passive light-squared bishop.} *

