{because Black has already started his pawn storm.}) d4 {Critical but incorrect. 
10...Qb6 is stronger.} 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 (11... Bxd4 12. Bxd4 Nxd4 13. Be4 $1) 12. 
Ne4 $1 {[%cal Bc2c3,Be4c5,Be4d6,Bd3e4,Ge3c5][%csl Rc5,Rd4,Re8,Ra8]} (12. Be4 $6 
{is inaccurate due to} 12... Nb6 $1) {White will win the piece back and have a 
positional advantage due to his space advantage and lead in development.} (12. 
Ne4 12... Nxc2 13. Bxc2 {White is better from the positional point of view with 
equal material.}) (12. Ne4 12... Bb6 $2 13. Nd6+ Kf8 14. Be4 {followed by Bxa8 
or Bxd4.}) (12. Ne4 12... Qb6 $2 13. Nxc5 Qxc5 14. c3) (12. Ne4 12... Bb7 $2 13. 
Bxd4 Bxd4 14. Nd6+) *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "French"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the French:"]
[Black "Steinitz with 7...Qb6"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4684455"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} Nf6 4. e5 {3... Nf6 is the Steinitz Variation. Black 
hits the e4-pawn, provoking White to advance. White gains space.} Nfd7 5. f4 
{White gains space and adds further support to the e5 pawn before playing Nf3.} 
c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 {White continues to support the d4-pawn. White has a space 
advantage, but Black has pressure on the center. Black's c-pawn is likely to be 
traded for White's d-pawn, which would give Black a central pawn majority but 
would give White an outpost on d4 for his knight.} Qb6 8. Na4 {Black increases 
the pressure against White's d4-pawn and threatens to capture on b2. The 
downside of this line is that Black exposes his queen before finishing his 
development. White takes advantage of Black's exposed queen with a double attack 
on c5 and b6.} Qa5+ {Black can't safely retreat his queen because the c5-pawn 
would be hanging, and 8... Qb4+ allows 9. c3 with tempo.} 9. c3 {White protects 
his knight and supports his center.} cxd4 (9... c4 {is playable, but after} 10. 
b4 {White will have a space advantage and Black will be relatively passive.}) 
10. b4 {White needs to play this move in order to support the c5-square, as 10. 
Nxd4 loses a piece to 10... b5.} Nxb4 (10... Qc7 11. Nxd4 {White has a space 
advantage and a lead in development.}) 11. cxb4 {“'In this line Black gives up 
a piece for three pawns, two of which are doubled. It has gone in and out of 
fashion, but the latest analysis indicates that Black is struggling to justify 
the investment of a knight.' - GM Parimarjan Negi”} Bxb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. 
Nxd2 {[%cal Bf1d3,Be1g1,Bh1f1,Gb7b5,Ga4b2][%csl Rc8] White will rapidly develop 
and can use his extra piece to fight for a kingside initiative. Black's extra 
central pawn is securely blockaded, so there isn't serious danger of Black 
making a queen anytime soon.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "French"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the French:"]
[Black "Rubinstein (Fort Knox)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4684456"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} dxe4 {The Rubinstein variation. Black gives opens the 
a8-h1 diagonal at the cost of increasing White's space advantage.} 4. Nxe4 Bd7 
{The Fort Knox. Black prepares to play ...Bc6, activating his light-squared 
bishop.} 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Neg5 {Simple developing moves such as 6. Bd3 followed by 
7. O-O give White a small and simple advantage, but I like 6. Neg5 better. White 
doesn't mask his intentions: he wants to fight for a kingside attack. One of 
White's main ideas is to sacrifice his knight on f7, follow up with Ng5+ (or 
Ne5+ if Black had played ...h6), and play against Black's king in the center. 
White can get away with this because he can quickly castle and Black is behind 
in development. Other than sacrificing ideas, White's immediate threat is to 
play 7. Ne5 followed by 8. Ngxf7, so Black has to take defensive measures.} Nd7 
{Black develops his queenside knight and guards the e5-square.} (6... Nf6 $2 7. 
Ne5) (6... h6 $2 7. Nxf7 Kxf7 8. Ne5+ {White will play Qh5 with a decisive 
attack.}) (6... Be7 7. Bd3 {White has the initiative and Black has to watch out 
for possible sacrifices.}) (6... Bd6 7. Nxf7 Kxf7 8. Ng5+ {White has an attack 
similar to the 6...Nd7 variation.}) 7. Nxf7 {White can follow up with Ng5+ and 
can easily win Black's e6-pawn, so this is a piece sacrifice for 2 pawns and the 
initiative.} Kxf7 8. Ng5+ {[%cal Bf1d3,Bd3c4,Gf7e8,Be1g1,Bh1f1,Bf1e1][%csl Re6] 
White will follow up with Bd3/Bc4 with O-O and Re1 with a powerful initiative. 
The Black king won't be able to leave the center for a long time.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
