[Black "French: Rubinstein"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4684457"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} dxe4 {The Rubinstein variation. Black gives opens the 
a8-h1 diagonal at the cost of increasing White's space advantage.} 4. Nxe4 Nd7 
{Black prepares to play 5... Ndf6.} (4... Nf6 $6 5. Nxf6+ Qxf6 6. Nf3 {The Black 
queen is a target and White is threatening to gain time attacking it with Bg5.}) 
5. g3 {One of Black's main ideas behind the Rubinstein variation is to develop 
his light-squared bishop on the long diagonal. Therefore, White aims to beat 
Black to that diagonal by playing Bg2 before Black can play ...Bb7.} Ngf6 6. 
Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Bg2 {[%cal Gg2a8,Bg1f3,Be1g1,Bh1f1,Bf1e1][%csl Rc8] White has a 
space advantage and a more active light-squared bishop. The burden of proof is 
on Black to demonstrate that he can equalize.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "French"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the French:"]
[Black "Winawer with 5...Ba5"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4684458"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} Bb4 {The Winawer Variation is Black's sharpest option, 
immediately pinning the c3-knight. The main drawback is that 3... Bb4 weakens 
the kingside dark squares, especially g7.} 4. e5 {White closes the center and 
makes a pawn chain which is aimed at the kingside, where White would like to 
attack. White wants to play Qg4 in order to target the weak g7 square, provoke 
Black to take on c3 (by playing a3) in order for White to win the bishop pair, 
and develop rapidly.} c5 {Black attacks the base of White's pawn chain.} 5. a3 
{White forces Black to commit his bishop.} Ba5 6. b4 $1 {White sacrifices a pawn 
to unpin his c3-knight. If Black accepts, White can play Nb5-d6+ with a powerful 
initiative.} cxb4 {6...cxd4 is stronger. This will be covered in the next 
variation.} 7. Nb5 bxa3+ {White threatens to play Nd6+, preventing Black from 
castling.} (7... b3 8. c3) 8. c3 {[%cal 
Bc1a3,Bb5d6,Bd1g4,Bg1f3,Bf1d3,Be1g1,Bh1f1][%csl Gf1,Gc1,Rd6,Re8] White creates a 
central pawn chain and can recapture on a3 shortly. Despite being down a pawn, 
White has the advantage due to his pawn center, easier development (he has open 
lines) White's threat of Nd6+, and Black's passive c8-bishop. White can prevent 
Black from castling with Nd6+ and finish his development with Ba3, Qg4, Nf3, 
Bd3, and O-O.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "French"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the French:"]
[Black "Winawer with 5...Ba5"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4704390"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} Bb4 {The Winawer Variation is Black's sharpest option, 
immediately pinning the c3-knight. The main drawback is that 3... Bb4 weakens 
the kingside dark squares, especially g7.} 4. e5 {White closes the center and 
makes a pawn chain which is aimed at the kingside, where White would like to 
attack. White wants to play Qg4 in order to target the weak g7 square, provoke 
Black to take on c3 (by playing a3) in order for White to win the bishop pair, 
and develop rapidly.} c5 {Black attacks the base of White's pawn chain.} 5. a3 
{White forces Black to commit his bishop.} Ba5 6. b4 $1 {White sacrifices a pawn 
to unpin his c3-knight. If Black accepts, White can play Nb5-d6+ with a powerful 
initiative.} cxd4 7. Qg4 ({The solid} 7. Nb5 {is also possible and requires less 
theory to learn, but probably won't give White as big of an advantage.}) Ne7 8. 
bxa5 {“'This is the main line. The next few moves are virtually forced.' - GM 
Parimarjan Negi”} dxc3 9. Qxg7 Rg8 10. Qxh7 {This is similar to the poisoned 
pawn variation in that White has the bishop pair and a passed h-pawn as 
long-term assets. If White is able to safely finish his development and secure 
his king without making too many concessions on the way, those positional 
advantages will give White the better game.} Nbc6 11. Nf3 Qc7 {Black keeps his 
queen close to the center and prevents Ng5 due to ...Qxe5+.} 12. Bf4 {White 
develops a piece and supports his e5-pawn.} Bd7 {Black develops a piece and 
prepares to castle queenside.} 13. a6 {It is useful to insert this move as Black 
is now unable to play ...Qxa5.} O-O-O 14. axb7+ Kb8 15. Qd3 {[%cal 
Bf1e2,Bf4g3,Rg8g4,Rg2g3,Be1g1,Bh1f1][%csl Gh2,Gf4,Gf1] White brings his queen 
back into the game. White is currently up material, has the bishop pair, and a 
passed h-pawn. Black is the one who will have to demonstrate dynamic 
compensation or else he will have a much worse position.} ({Critical is} 15. Qd3 
15... Rg4 16. g3 Ng6 17. Qxc3 Nxf4 18. h3 $1 {and after the complications White 
will be up a pawn.}) (15. Qd3 15... d4 16. Be2 Rxg2 (16... Nf5 17. O-O) 17. Bg3) 
*

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "French"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the French:"]
[Black "Winawer with 5...cxd4"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4684460"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} Bb4 {The Winawer Variation is Black's sharpest option, 
immediately pinning the c3-knight. The main drawback is that 3... Bb4 weakens 
the kingside dark squares, especially g7.} 4. e5 {White closes the center and 
makes a pawn chain which is aimed at the kingside, where White would like to 
attack. White wants to play Qg4 in order to target the weak g7 square, provoke 
Black to take on c3 (by playing a3) in order for White to win the bishop pair, 
and develop rapidly.} c5 {Black attacks the base of White's pawn chain.} 5. a3 
{White forces Black to commit his bishop.} cxd4 {“'The main drawbacks of 
Black's system are that he gives away his dark-squared bishop without really 
spoiling White's structure, and also opening the position a bit more than 
necessary, especially for the c1-bishop and the a1-rook. The fact that the 
mainline sees White giving up a pawn does little to enhance the appeal of 
Black's system.' - GM Parimarjan Negi”} 6. axb4 dxc3 7. Qg4 {[%cal 
Bg1f3,Bf1d3,Be1g1,Bh1f1,Ba1a3][%csl Rg7,Gf1,Gc1]} ({Negi's recommended} 7. Nf3 
{is similar, though White's queen won't be as active.}) {White sacrifices his 
b2-pawn in order to support his e5-pawn and get a lead in development. Given 
that White has a space advantage, a lead in development, and the bishop pair, 
White will have more than enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn. White 
would rather not take on c3 because that would give him some weakness. White 
will rapidly develop with Nf3, Bd3, and O-O. To provoke ...cxb2, White will 
likely play Ra3. Black will need to make a concession (...Kf8 or ...g6) to save 
his g7-pawn.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
