[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4684461"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} Bb4 {The Winawer Variation is Black's sharpest option, 
immediately pinning the c3-knight. The main drawback is that 3... Bb4 weakens 
the kingside dark squares, especially g7.} 4. e5 {White closes the center and 
makes a pawn chain which is aimed at the kingside, where White would like to 
attack. White wants to play Qg4 in order to target the weak g7 square, provoke 
Black to take on c3 (by playing a3) in order for White to win the bishop pair, 
and develop rapidly.} c5 {Black attacks the base of White's pawn chain.} 5. a3 
{White forces Black to commit his bishop.} Bxc3+ {Black gives up his bishop pair 
in order to double White's c-pawns. Now that Black's dark-squared bishop is 
gone, the g7-pawn is weaker.} 6. bxc3 Qc7 {While 6... Ne7 is the mainline, 6... 
Qc7 is sometimes played.} 7. Qg4 f5 {The only critical line of independent 
value.} (7... Ne7 8. Bd3 {transposes into} 6... Ne7 {.}) (7... cxd4 $2 8. Qxg7 
{White will have a decisive material advantage.}) 8. Qg3 cxd4 {“'This time 
Black doesn't want to sacrifice anything, so he exchanges in the center before 
developing his knight to e7, thus preventing a capture on g7 in view of the 
subsequent check on c3. There is an obvious downside, as the pawn exchange 
solves White's main problem of the doubled c-pawns, while giving him a free hand 
to develop his pieces on ideal squares.' - GM Parimarjan Negi”} (8... Ne7 9. 
Qxg7 Rg8 10. Qxh7 cxd4 {favors White after} 11. Ne2 {or 11. Kd1}) 9. cxd4 Ne7 
10. c3 O-O 11. Ne2 {[%cal Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Bh5h6,Be2f4][%csl Gf1,Gc1,Rg7] White will 
fight for a kingside initiative by pushing his h-pawn and playing Nf4. At some 
point Black will likely meet h6 with ...g6, significantly weakening his 
dark-squares.} *

