and will follow up with Qh5 or Qh4.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "French"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the French:"]
[Black "Winawer with 6...Ne7 7.Qg4 0-0"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4684463"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} Bb4 {The Winawer Variation is Black's sharpest option, 
immediately pinning the c3-knight. The main drawback is that 3... Bb4 weakens 
the kingside dark squares, especially g7.} 4. e5 {White closes the center and 
makes a pawn chain which is aimed at the kingside, where White would like to 
attack. White wants to play Qg4 in order to target the weak g7 square, provoke 
Black to take on c3 (by playing a3) in order for White to win the bishop pair, 
and develop rapidly.} c5 {Black attacks the base of White's pawn chain.} 5. a3 
{White forces Black to commit his bishop.} Bxc3+ {Black gives up his bishop pair 
in order to double White's c-pawns. Now that Black's dark-squared bishop is 
gone, the g7-pawn is weaker.} 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. Qg4 {White targets the g7-pawn.} 
O-O {A risky line, as Black castles into an attack. White develops his 
light-squared bishop and takes aim at Black's h7-pawn. “'This used to be the 
most heavily debated line in the French, whereas the Poisoned Pawn Variation was 
considered excessively risky and was generally avoided by strong professionals. 
But as the theory evolved, we saw a complete turnaround in the respective 
fortunes of the two systems, and nowadays there are not too many strong 
grandmasters who dare go down this path with Black.' - GM Parimarjan Negi ”} 
8. Bd3 Nbc6 9. Qh5 {White forces ...Ng6 before Black can play ...c4 so that 
White will have the option of playing Bxg6.} Ng6 10. Nf3 {White threatens Ng5, 
so Black must act quickly.} Qc7 {Black develops his queen and threatens to 
capture twice on d4 due to the ...Qc3+ fork.} 11. Be3 {White develops his bishop 
and lends support to the d4-square, so that ...Nxd4 (after ...cxd4 and cxd4) can 
be met by Bxd4 (defending the c3-square).} c4 {Delaying this move will allow 
White to improve the circumstances with Ng5, as ...h6 weakens the g6-knight. 
“'With this move Black avoids the constantly annoying threats involving h2-h4 
and targeting the g6-knight, as he forces White to drastically alter the 
position by exchanging on g6 (retreating to e2 is possible, but it is not a 
serious try for an advantage) . Unfortunately for Black, there is no respite 
from White's aggressive plans, as the ensuing middlegame with opposite colored 
bishops gives White plenty of scope to aim for the maximum on the kingside.' - 
GM Parimarjan Negi”} 12. Bxg6 fxg6 (12... hxg6 {would allow White to get a 
similar sort of attack without giving Black the f-file. Black needs the f-file 
in order to fight for counterplay.}) 13. Qg4 {[%cal 
Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Be1d2,Bf3g5,Ba1g1,Gg4e2,Gg2g4][%csl Rg6,Rg8] White will fight for a 
kingside initiative with moves like h4-h5 and Ng5. The White king will be 
reasonably safe on d2 and the a1-rook can be included in the attack with Rg1 and 
g4 (White will play Qh3 or Qe2 before g4).} ({A sample continuation could be} 
13. Qg4 13... Qf7 14. Ng5 Qe8 15. h4 {with the initiative. “'At this point, 
Black has to make a pivotal decision. The normal thing is of course to play 
...h6, it's scary to have a knight hovering so close to your king, but at the 
same time moving the h-pawn creates new targets. Therefore some players, 
including Vallejo, have ignored the knight and delayed ...h6 for a while. Before 
analyzing any further, I would like to highlight the main attacking plan that 
you should know if you play this variation. If the knight remains on g5, then 
you can play Qe2, g2-g4 and h4-h5. If Black has not played ...h6, then ...gxh5 
can often be met by Nxh7!, followed by a slow but deadly exploitation of the 
open h-file. If the moves ...h6 and Nh3 have been included, White can go for the 
same attacking plan, advancing the pawns to g4 and h5. If Black responds with 
...gxh5, then White does not recapture but goes g4-g5!, creating inroads on the 
dark squares. Finally, if Black tries to block the kingside by meeting h4-h5 
with ...g5, then White will prepare f2-f4, opening the f-file with chances of a 
later g4-g5. While all of this is going on, it is important not to forget about 
the queenside where Black may look to prepare a counterattack with ...b4. 
Generally the White king will go to d2 to allow the second rook to join the 
attack. If Black proceeds with his plan of ...b4 and ...bxc3+, do not be afraid 
to recapture on c3 with the king! Unless the a3-pawn can be targeted quickly, 
the king will often be safe on c3, at least for the few moves needed to break 
through on the kingside.' - GM Parimarjan Negi ”}) *

