[White "Introduction to the French:"]
[Black "Winawer with 6...Ne7 7.Qg4 Qc7 8.Bd3 c4"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 French"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4684466"]

1. e4 e6 {Black prepares to set up a pawn center with ...d5. The drawback of 
1... e6 (the French defense) is that Black restricts his light-squared bishop.} 
2. d4 {White occupies the center with pawns.} d5 3. Nc3 {The most active way of 
defending the e4-pawn.} Bb4 {The Winawer Variation is Black's sharpest option, 
immediately pinning the c3-knight. The main drawback is that 3... Bb4 weakens 
the kingside dark squares, especially g7.} 4. e5 {White closes the center and 
makes a pawn chain which is aimed at the kingside, where White would like to 
attack. White wants to play Qg4 in order to target the weak g7 square, provoke 
Black to take on c3 (by playing a3) in order for White to win the bishop pair, 
and develop rapidly.} c5 {Black attacks the base of White's pawn chain.} 5. a3 
{White forces Black to commit his bishop.} Bxc3+ {Black gives up his bishop pair 
in order to double White's c-pawns. Now that Black's dark-squared bishop is 
gone, the g7-pawn is weaker.} 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. Qg4 {White targets the g7-pawn.} 
Qc7 {The Poisoned Pawn variation. Black sacrifices his g and h-pawns in order to 
get a counterattack down the c-file starting with ...cxd4 (threatening 
...Qc3+).} 8. Bd3 {The roles are reversed - White sacrifices material to 
increase his lead in development. “'White postpones the capture of Black's 
kingside pawns and may even give up a pawn or two. In return, he keeps a safe 
king, and will try to exploit the dark-square weaknesses to generate an 
initiative against the black king. This is an important psychological 
achievement, as who would not prefer to attack?' - GM Parimarjan Negi ”} ({In 
the mainlines after} 8. Qxg7 Rg8 9. Qxh7 cxd4 10. Ne2 {Black easily completes 
development and White has trouble developing his kingside. White is up material 
and can fight for a win with his passed h-pawn, but I would prefer to be better 
developed. Therefore, I prefer 8.Bd3 over 8.Qxg7, intending to meet ...cxd4 with 
Ne2. The positions can be similar if Black does not accept the pawn sacrifices, 
but White would be able to develop his kingside.}) c4 {“'This leads to a 
thematic blocked French structure, which I regard as something of a 
psychological victory for White. The point is that, by playing 7... Qc7, Black 
invited a highly double-edged battle, but his last move veered away from that by 
entering a much more slow and staid variation. At the same time, White needs a 
good plan, as it is easy to get confused about the placement of pieces in this 
variation. As long as he is armed with a clear strategy, White should have good 
chances.' - GM Parimarjan Negi”} 9. Be2 Nf5 {“'This time Black hopes to 
carry out a long castling followed by a subsequent ...f6 to create some 
instability on the kingside. White has tried various plans, including a quick 
pawn advance with g2-g4 and f2-f4, or exchanging a pair of knights with Nf3-h4, 
or other concrete ideas. However, I think the most effective strategy for White 
is to neutralize Black's counterplay. This can be achieved by maneuvering the 
knight to the h5-square, after which Black's hopes of kingside counterplay is 
dead. We should also remember that ...f6 will open up the game for the 
dark-squared bishop, so even if Black does manage to get this move in, White 
does not have to fear it if his pieces are well placed.' - GM Parimarjan 
Negi”} 10. Bd1 {[%cal Bg4h3,Bg2g4,Bf2f4,Bg1e2,Be2g3][%csl Rf5,Re8] White 
prepares to meet ...Qa5 with Ne2, avoiding an x-ray attack of ...Qa5 against 
Bd2. “'Black can respond in a few different ways. If he castles on the 
kingside, White has the attractive plan of Ne2, f2-f4, O-O, Qh3, g2-g4, and Ng3 
when his pieces coordinate perfectly to support a massive attack. If Black opts 
for long castling, the White knight will go to g3, when ...Nxg3 runs into the 
annoying fxg3. Black's only counterplay is related to the ...f6 break, but this 
will open up the position for White's dark-squared bishop, while Ng3 will block 
any play down the g-file. If Black refrains from ...f6, it will be difficult for 
him to do anything, while White can improve his position with plans like a3-a4 
and Ba3, and perhaps Nh5.' - GM Parimarjan Negi”} *

