the mainlines after} 8. Qxg7 Rg8 9. Qxh7 cxd4 10. Ne2 {Black easily completes 
development and White has trouble developing his kingside. White is up material 
and can fight for a win with his passed h-pawn, but I would prefer to be better 
developed. Therefore, I prefer 8.Bd3 over 8.Qxg7, intending to meet ...cxd4 with 
Ne2. The positions can be similar if Black does not accept the pawn sacrifices, 
but White would be able to develop his kingside.}) cxd4 {Black must enter 
concrete play or else White will be positionally better (bishop pair and 
kingside space/initiative) for free.} 9. Ne2 {White protects his c3-pawn to 
defend against ...Qxc3+.} dxc3 10. Qxg7 Rg8 11. Qxh7 Qxe5 12. h4 {White begins 
to advance his passed h-pawn and supports the g5-square for his bishop.} (12. 
Bf4 {is also playable but less flexible because sometimes White wants to play 
Bg5 in one move instead of two.}) Nd7 {Black controls the f6-square, giving him 
the chance to play ...f6 if White plays Bf4 followed by Bg5.} 13. Bf4 Qf6 {13... 
Qh8 gives Black an inferior version of the same endgame because White's bishop 
is better placed on f4 (...e5 is more loosening than ...f6).} 14. Bg5 Qh8 (14... 
Qe5 15. Bxe7) 15. Qxh8 Rxh8 16. Nxc3 {[%cal Be1c1,Ba1d1,Bg2g4,Bh4h5,Bc3b5][%csl 
Gh4,Rg5,Rd3] “'White has the more active pieces, a strong dark-squared bishop, 
and of course the passed h-pawn. On the other hand, Black has a strong center 
and a more compact structure.' - GM Parimarjan Negi”} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the"]
[Black "Sicilian: Taimanov"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4705030"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian is one of Black's most dynamic options against 1. e4. 
Black controls the d4-square with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn, aiming to 
create an imbalance in pawn majorities if White plays d4.} 2. Nf3 {White 
develops and plans to open the center with d4 in order to exploit his lead in 
development.} e6 {This is one of three main ways for Black to play after 2. 
Nf3.} 3. d4 {White opens the center in order to highlight his lead in 
development and to fight for the initiative.} cxd4 {Black trades his c-pawn for 
White's d-pawn, creating a central pawn majority.} 4. Nxd4 Nc6 {The Taimanov.} 
5. Nc3 {[%cal Bc1e3,Bd1d2,Be1c1,Ba1d1,Bf2f3,Bg2g4,Bg4g5] White can castle 
queenside and play for an attack in the style of the English Attack (Be3, Qd2, 
O-O-O, f3, g4-g5) or castle kingside and play in the style of the Scheveningen 
(Be2, O-O, Be3, f4).} ({Playing for} 5. c4 {isn't as strong here as it is after 
4...a6 because Black better developed. He is able to use this development to 
fight for the initiative with} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 {with ...d5. Since Black can 
achieve an early ...d5, the main point behind c4 has been defused and Black 
would have free development.}) *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the"]
[Black "Sicilian: Kan (Hedgehog)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4705029"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian is one of Black's most dynamic options against 1. e4. 
Black controls the d4-square with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn, aiming to 
create an imbalance in pawn majorities if White plays d4.} 2. Nf3 {White 
develops and plans to open the center with d4 in order to exploit his lead in 
development.} e6 {This is one of three main ways for Black to play after 2. Nf3. 
2... e6 gives Black a lot of flexibility to decide where he wants to place his 
dark-squared bishop. White opens the center in order to highlight his lead in 
development and to fight for the initiative.} 3. d4 {White opens the center in 
order to highlight his lead in development and to fight for the initiative.} 
cxd4 {Black trades his c-pawn for White's d-pawn, creating a central pawn 
majority.} 4. Nxd4 a6 {The Kan. Black prepares ...b5.} 5. c4 {White gains space 
in the center before playing Nc3, impeding Black's ...d5 and ...b5 breaks. This 
pawn structure is most likely going to transpose into the Hedgehog pawn 
structure and is different from the Maroczy bind as Black is usually not going 
to fianchetto his kingside bishop (he played ...e6 instead of ...g6). This leads 
to some key differences: since Black isn't pressuring the d4-knight, his plan in 
the mainline Maroczy bind (...Nxd4 with ...Bc6, pressure on long-diagonal) is no 
longer viable. Instead, Black generally wants to place his pawns on a6, b6, d6, 
and e6 in order to guard key central squares and intends to develop his pieces 
in a harmonious way which exerts pressure on White's center. He hopes that White 
will prematurely attack, where Black's pieces will be well-placed for a 
counter-attack. Black isn't forced to go for the Hedgehog plan, but it's his 
best chance for counterplay in the 5. c4 variation.} Nf6 6. Nc3 {White defends 
his e4-pawn. Now that the e4-square is defended by a piece, White is threatening 
to play e5.} (6. e5 $2 Qa5+ {wins a pawn.}) Qc7 {Black defends the e5-square 
with his queen.} (6... Bb4 7. Qd3 Qc7 8. a3 {Black will have to lose time or the 
bishop pair, since the complications after} 8... Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Nxe4 10. Nb5 $1 
axb5 11. Qxg7 Rf8 12. Bh6 {favor White. For more information, see the full 
course.}) 7. a3 {White prevents ...Bb4. Sidelines with ...Bb4 have been 
prevented, now Black is almost certain to play this in Hedgehog style. Other 
than preventing ...Bb4, a3 is a useful move to make in the Hedgehog because 
White wants to attack on the queenside.} Be7 8. Be2 {7... d6 is similar and is 
likely to transpose. Both sides generally follow the same development plan at 
this point regardless of the move order.} O-O 9. Be3 d6 10. O-O b6 11. f3 {White 
generally wants to play f3 in order to secure his center before beginning his 
queenside attack.} Bb7 12. Qd2 Nbd7 13. Rfd1 Rac8 14. Rac1 Rfe8 15. b4 {[%cal 
Rc4c5,Rd6d5,Bg1h1,Be2f1,Bd2f2,Bc3a4,Bd4b3,Gc7b8,Gb8a8,Ge7d8,Gd8c7] This is a 
normal Hedgehog position. Black plans to maneuver his pieces in a way that 
prepares for a possible ...d5 break (...Qb8 with ...Bd8-c7, possibly play ...h5 
(White should usually defend against the threat of ...h4 with Bf2 or Qe1) 
intending ...h4-h3 to make a kingside weakness), and wait for an opportunity to 
get the ...d5 break at a favorable moment. White plans to prepare the c5 break 
to open the queenside. This can be done by combining prophylaxis (moves like 
Kh1, Bf1, and Bg1 - defending the kingside in case Black plays ...d5) with 
concrete preparation aiming pieces pieces at the c5-square with moves like Nb3, 
Na4, and Qf2).} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the"]
[Black "Sicilian: Sveshnikov"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4705034"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian is one of Black's most dynamic options against 1. e4. 
Black controls the d4-square with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn, aiming to 
create an imbalance in pawn majorities if White plays d4.} 2. Nf3 {White 
develops and plans to open the center with d4 in order to exploit his lead in 
development.} Nc6 {Black stays flexible by not committing to a specific pawn 
structure. White opens the center in order to highlight his lead in development 
and to fight for the initiative.} 3. d4 cxd4 {Black trades his c-pawn for 
White's d-pawn, creating a central pawn majority.} 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 {The 
Sveshnikov. Black gains central space at the cost of weakening the d5 and 
d6-squares. The Sveshnikov used to be seen as positionally unsound, but Black 
revived it with concrete ideas. “'To be honest, I was rather amused when in 
the very first game of the match I saw the move 5... e5 on the board. Indeed, to 
weaken the key d5-square in such a way! My opponent obviously had a poor 
understanding of chess and did not read books at all.' - GM Gennadi 
Timoshchenko”} 6. Ndb5 {White is essentially forced to play 6. Ndb5 because 
retreating allows ...Bb4 which gives Black active play and 6. Nf5 allows the 
thematic pawn break ...d5!} d6 {Black prevents 7. Nd6+, which would have won the 
bishop pair.} 7. Bg5 {The knight on f6 is the main defender of the weakened 
d5-square, so White aims to trade it off.} a6 {Black aims to obtain some 
compensation for his weak d5 square by forcing White's knight to the side of the 
board, where it will be temporarily out of play. If Black delays this for just 
one move, White can play 8. Nd5 and then bring his other knight into the game 
with Nbc3. a3 is the only safe square for White's knight.} 8. Na3 b5 {8... b5 
prevents 9. Nc4, which would bring White's knight on a3 back into the game. 
Black also threatens ...b4, winning a piece.} 9. Nd5 {White centralizes his 
knight. He is ready to take on f6 with the bishop to consolidate the d5-knight's 
powerful position.} Be7 {Black breaks the pin and threatens to play ...Nxd5.} 
10. Bxf6 {White trades off his dark-squared bishop, leaving Black on the wrong 
end of a strong knight vs. bad bishop situation.} Bxf6 {10... gxf6 would weaken 
the kingside too much.} 11. c3 {[%cal Ba3c2,Bc2e3,Ba2a4][%csl Gd5,Rb5] 11. c3 
prevents ...Nd4 and prepares to bring White's a3 knight back into the game via 
c2 and e3. The position is very unbalanced. Black has central weaknesses but has 
the bishop pair to compensate. Black has gained queenside space, but this could 
be targeted by a2-a4 at a key moment to try to create some weaknesses.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the"]
[Black "Sicilian: Kalashnikov"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4705031"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian is one of Black's most dynamic options against 1. e4. 
Black controls the d4-square with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn, aiming to 
create an imbalance in pawn majorities if White plays d4.} 2. Nf3 {White 
develops and plans to open the center with d4 in order to exploit his lead in 
development.} Nc6 {Black stays flexible by not committing to a specific pawn 
structure.} 3. d4 {White opens the center in order to highlight his lead in 
development and to fight for the initiative.} cxd4 {Black trades his c-pawn for 
White's d-pawn, creating a central pawn majority.} 4. Nxd4 e5 {Black wants to 
get a Sveshnikov-like position without playing ...Nf6 because Bg5 would remove 
the defender of the d5-square. This variation is known as the Kalashnikov.} 5. 
Nb5 {Just like in the Sveshnikov, White threatens to play Nd6+, forcing Black to 
block his dark-squared bishop inside his pawn chain with ...d6.} d6 6. N1c3 
{White increases his control over the d5-square.} a6 {Just like in the 
Sveshnikov, Black should rush with ...a6 and ...b5 to restrict White's knight, 
otherwise White could bring it into the game with Nd5 and Nbc3 or Na3-c4.} 7. 
Na3 b5 {Other 7th moves allow White to play Bc4, bringing his knight back to the 
center.} 8. Nd5 {White occupies the weak d5-square and prevents ...b4 from being 
a fork.} Nge7 {Black avoids a Sveshnikov transposition (and prevents Bg5 from 
being as effective as it would be if Black played ...Nf6), but cramps his 
development.} (8... Nf6 9. Bg5 {transposes into the Sveshnikov.}) 9. c4 {White 
gains central space and attacks Black's b5-pawn. This move takes advantage of 
Black not playing ...Nf6, because if Black has played ...Nf6, he would be 
attacking White's e4-pawn (nullifying c4 for the time being).} Nd4 10. Be3 
{White applies pressure on Black's d4-knight. In order to develop his kingside, 
Black is forced to play ...Nxd5.} Nxd5 11. cxd5 {White now has a central space 
advantage, can easily finish his development (Bd3, O-O, Nc2), and can later open 
the position with f4. Black is the one who has to prove compensation for White's 
space advantage and easy plan.} Be7 12. Bd3 {[%cal 
Be1g1,Bh1f1,Bf2f4,Bd1d2,Ba3c2,Bc2d4][%csl Gd5,Ge4,Rd4] White's position is 
slightly better due to his space advantage. His plan is to finish his 
development (O-O, Qd2, Nc2), open the position with f4, and consider taking on 
d4 (with his knight) to damage Black's pawn structure.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the Sicilian:"]
[Black "Accelerated Dragon (Maroczy Bind)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4705032"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian is one of Black's most dynamic options against 1. e4. 
Black controls the d4-square with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn, aiming to 
create an imbalance in pawn majorities if White plays d4.} 2. Nf3 {White 
develops and plans to open the center with d4 in order to exploit his lead in 
development.} Nc6 {Black stays flexible by not committing to a specific pawn 
structure.} 3. d4 {White opens the center in order to highlight his lead in 
development and to fight for the initiative.} cxd4 {Black trades his c-pawn for 
White's d-pawn, creating a central pawn majority.} 4. Nxd4 g6 {The Accelerated 
Dragon. Black aims for a Dragon position where he can play ...d5 in one move 
instead of two. The consequences of delaying ...Nf6 is that White can play c4 
before Nc3, obtaining a space advantage.} 5. c4 {The Maroczy bind. White gains 
space and prevents Black's ...d5 and ...b5 breaks. “'Geza Maroczy left a 
strange legacy: the discovery that certain pawn formations can impose a near 
decisive cramp on one's opponent.' - Bobby Fischer (Former World Champion, 
1972-1975)”} Nf6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O (7... Ng4 8. Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 {Black 
has successfully traded a pair of minor pieces, but White still has more space 
and easier development.}) 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Bd7 (9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bd7 11. Qd3 
$1 {White doesn't need to play f3 to support his center, he can play f4 instead. 
Qd2 is usually more ideal than Qd3 with Black's queenside knight on c6, as Black 
would be able to meet Qd3 with ...Ne5, but without the possibility of ...Ne5, 
Qd3 is more logical.}) 10. Nc2 {[%cal Bf2f3,Bd1d2,Ba1c1,Bf1d1,Bb2b3,Bf3f4][%csl 
Gc4,Ge4] White avoids the trade of knights because he has more space. White's c4 
and e4 pawns really restrict Black, making it harder for Black to find a clear 
plan. White's plan is to either support his center (f3) or fight for a kingside 
attack (f4) combined with finishing his development (Qd2, Rac1, Rfd1). For a 
model game in this line, see *Sam Shankland vs. Gadir Guseinov*.} *

