[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the Sicilian:"]
[Black "Accelerated Dragon (Maroczy Bind)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4705033"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian is one of Black's most dynamic options against 1. e4. 
Black controls the d4-square with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn, aiming to 
create an imbalance in pawn majorities if White plays d4.} 2. Nf3 {White 
develops and plans to open the center with d4 in order to exploit his lead in 
development.} Nc6 {Black stays flexible by not committing to a specific pawn 
structure.} 3. d4 {White opens the center in order to highlight his lead in 
development and to fight for the initiative.} cxd4 {Black trades his c-pawn for 
White's d-pawn, creating a central pawn majority.} 4. Nxd4 g6 {The Accelerated 
Dragon. Black aims for a Dragon position where he can play ...d5 in one move 
instead of two. The consequences of delaying ...Nf6 is that White can play c4 
before Nc3, obtaining a space advantage.} 5. c4 {The Maroczy bind. White gains 
space and prevents Black's ...d5 and ...b5 breaks. “'Geza Maroczy left a 
strange legacy: the discovery that certain pawn formations can impost a near 
decisive cramp on one's opponent.' - Bobby Fischer (Former World Champion, 
1972-1975)”} Nf6 6. Nc3 Nxd4 {Black trades a pair of knights and provokes 
White's queen to the center where it could be exposed. This avoids White's Nc2 
setup, here we should choose something more aggressive to try to punish Black's 
early ...Nxd4.} ({In the main lines with} 6... Bg7 7. Be3 {Black usually delays} 
...Nxd4 {for a few moves and White has not yet committed to Be3.}) 7. Qxd4 d6 
{Preventing e5.} 8. Be2 Bg7 9. Bg5 {Bg5 is well placed if White chooses an 
aggressive plan with f4 with f5 or e5.} O-O 10. Qd2 {Getting off of the long 
diagonal. Discovered attacks could have become possible at some point.} Be6 11. 
O-O {White intends on securing the queenside (Rc1 with b3) then fighting for a 
kingside initiative with f4-f5.} (11. Rc1 {is another move order that is likely 
to transpose.}) Qa5 12. Rac1 Rfc8 13. b3 a6 14. f4 {[%cal 
Bf4f5,Be4e5,Bd2e3,Bg1h1][%csl Ge4,Gf4,Re6] White has a powerful initiative and 
Black doesn't have sufficient counterplay. White can play f5 next or even 
prepare it with various prophylactic moves such as Kh1 and Qe3.} ({A trap that 
many of my opponents have fallen for runs} 14. f4 14... b5 $6 15. f5 $1 Bd7 $2 
16. e5 {White has a decisive initiative because} 16... dxe5 {loses to} 17. Bxf6 
Bxf6 18. Qxd7 {.}) *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the"]
[Black "Sicilian: Dragon (Classical)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4705036"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian is one of Black's most dynamic options against 1. e4. 
Black controls the d4-square with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn, aiming to 
create an imbalance in pawn majorities if White plays d4.} 2. Nf3 {White 
develops and plans to open the center with d4 in order to exploit his lead in 
development.} d6 {2... d6 fights for control of the e5-square so that Black can 
play ...Nf6 without having to worry about e5 ideas.} 3. d4 {White opens the 
center in order to highlight his lead in development and to fight for the 
initiative.} cxd4 {Black trades his c-pawn for White's d-pawn, creating a 
central pawn majority.} 4. Nxd4 {White recaptures the pawn and establishes a 
strong knight on d4. Nxd4 is the most natural recapture as 4. Qxd4 would allow 
Black to develop and gain time on the queen with 4... Nc6.} Nf6 {Black develops 
with tempo. Delaying this move would allow White to increase his space advantage 
with c4 before playing Nc3, restricting Black's activity and preventing the 
...d5/...b5 breaks.} 5. Nc3 {White develops a piece and protects his d4-pawn. 5. 
Nc3 is superior to 5. Bd3 because it restricts Black from playing the ...d5 
break.} g6 6. Be3 {Black prepares to fianchetto his kingside bishop which would 
be very active on the open long diagonal. This signifies the Dragon Variation. 
The consequences of 5... g6 is that White now has a hook to open the h-file 
(h4-h5), increasing his prospects for a kingside attack. White intends to 
rapidly develop (f3, Qd2, Bc4, O-O-O) . After rapidly development, White would 
like to exchange dark-squared bishops (Bh6-xg7) in order to weaken the 
dark-squares near the Black king (h6, g7, h8) which can be exploited with 
White's queen and h1-rook after opening the h-file (h4-h5). This plan is known 
as the Yugoslav attack. “'White's attack plays itself... weak players even 
beat Grandmasters with it.' - Bobby Fischer (Former World Champion, 
1972-1975)”} Bg7 (6... Ng4 7. Bb5+ $1 {White wins material because} 7... Bd7 
{loses a piece to} 8. Qxg4 {.}) 7. f3 {White prepares Qd2 by preventing ...Ng4.} 
O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 (8... d5 $6 9. e5 Nfd7 10. f4 {White has a space advantage and 
superior center control.}) 9. Bc4 {White prevents the ...d5 break and prepares 
to castle queenside.} Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 {This is a sharp position where 
both sides have clear plans. Black aims to attack White's queenside, where 
White's king is. Black usually plays ...Ne5-Nc4 to gain the bishop pair, and 
sometimes sacrifices the exchange with ...Rxc3 in order to expose White's 
queenside (if White's queen leaves d2 with a premature Bh6 and ...Bxh6). Black's 
queenside attack is helped by Black's fianchettoed bishop bearing pressure down 
the queenside. White's plan is to open the h file (g4 with h4 and h5, or 
sometimes h4-h5 without g4 as a pawn sacrifice), trade dark squared bishops, and 
attack Black's kingside. White's plan is rather straightforward, so it can be 
very difficult to defend Black's position.} Ne5 {The mainline - and also 
unsound. White's attack is faster because 5...g6 made a weakness. Black should 
have changed the nature of the position with 11... Nxd4.} (11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 
b5 $1 {this is why Black exchanged on d4. Now Black's attack is faster so White 
shifts back to the center, which Black weakened with ...Nxd4} 13. Nd5 $1 {with 
complications that will be covered later in this course.}) 12. Kb1 $1 {Improving 
White's king safety before committing to anything else. Many of Black's 
dangerous attacking options (checks on the c1-h6 diagonal, Black's thematic 
exchange sacrifice with ...Rxc3 with ...Qa5 (or ...Qc7) with ...Qxc3 doesn't 
threaten ...Qa1+ if White's king is on b1) are less powerful. Now Black has to 
make a commitment. Black doesn't have any waiting move that is as useful as 12. 
Kb1.} (12. h4 $6 h5 13. g4 hxg4 14. h5 Nxh5 15. Bh6 e6 16. Rdg1 Qf6 17. fxg4 
{would give White a winning initiative if it weren't for} 17... Bxh6 $1 18. Qxh6 
Qf4+ $1 {trading queens. This is why the White king would rather be on b1. It's 
also useful for other reasons, such as if Black plays the standard ...Rxc3 
sacrifice (after Bh6 and ...Bxh6 with Qxh6) followed by ...Qa5-xc3 (if the White 
king was on b1 there would not be a threat of ...Qa1+ with ...Qxd4+).}) Re8 {The 
mainline. Black makes a flexible waiting move of his own, now Nd5 won't tie the 
Black queen to the e7-pawn. Unfortunately for Black 12... Re8 allows White's 
idea and Black is now more or less losing by force.} (12... a6 {intending ...b5 
loses in more or less the same way Black loses after} 12... Re8 {.}) 13. h4 h5 
{As shown by *Karpov vs. Korchnoi 1984*, allowing h4-h5 is too dangerous.} 14. 
g4 hxg4 {The only consistent move. If Black does not play this White will open 
the g-file with gxh5 without needing to sacrifice a pawn.} 15. h5 Nxh5 {The 
consistent follow up. Black must capture the pawn or White will get the same 
sort of dangerous play without sacrificing the pawn.} 16. Bh6 {16. Bh6 is 
stronger than 16. Rhg1 (which is still dangerous) because White can respond to 
the exchange sacrifice 16... Rxc3 17. bxc3 Qc7 with a counter exchange sacrifice 
18. Rxh5 followed by 19. Rh1. White will usually play Rdg1 anyways, but Bh6 is 
slightly more accurate because occasionally it might be better for White to do 
something else (such as Rxh5 followed by Rh1) whereas White should always play 
Bh6 in this type of position in order to trade Black's main defender of the 
kingside. Summary: Both 16. Rhg1 and 16. Bh6 are strong attacking moves, but 16. 
Bh6 is more flexible.} e6 17. Rdg1 Qf6 {The main move by far. Black aims to play 
...Qf6 to bring another piece to the defense of the kingside. Deviations on this 
line are analyzed in the full course.} 18. fxg4 Bxh6 19. Qxh6 Qg7 20. Qd2 Nf6 
21. g5 Nh5 22. Nce2 {[%cal Be2g3,Gh5g3,Gg1g3,Bg3h3,Bd2f4,Bf4f6][%csl Rg8] White 
has a decisive attack. According to chess.com's database, White has won all the 
games in this position (11/11). White's plan is to trade knights with Ng3, 
double rooks on the h file, trade queens (Qf4 with Qf6), and checkmate Black on 
the h file. Black can't stop this without making serious concessions worth more 
than the pawn White sacrificed. White can either meet ...e5 with Nf5! (usually a 
decisive breakthrough) or Ne2-c3-d5 with good control of the d5 square. 
Stockfish doesn't immediately notice that White is winning but eventually 
realizes that White's attack is decisive.} *

