{loses a piece to} 8. Qxg4 {.}) {White prepares Qd2 by preventing ...Ng4.} 7. f3 
O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 (8... d5 $6 9. e5 Nfd7 10. f4 {White has a space advantage and 
superior center control.}) 9. Bc4 {White prevents the ...d5 break and prepares 
to castle queenside.} Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 {This is a sharp position where 
both sides have clear plans. Black aims to attack White's queenside, where 
White's king is. Black usually plays ...Ne5-Nc4 to gain the bishop pair, and 
sometimes sacrifices the exchange with ...Rxc3 in order to expose White's 
queenside (if White's queen leaves d2 with a premature Bh6 and ...Bxh6). Black's 
queenside attack is helped by Black's fianchettoed bishop baring pressure down 
the queenside. White's plan is to open the h file (g4 with h4 and h5, or 
sometimes h4-h5 without g4 as a pawn sacrifice), trade dark squared bishops, and 
attack Black's kingside. White's plan is rather straightforward, so it can be 
very difficult to defend Black's position.} Ne5 {The mainline - and also 
unsound. White's attack is faster because 5...g6 made a weakness. Black should 
