b5 $1 {this is why Black exchanged on d4. Now Black's attack is faster so White 
shifts back to the center, which Black weakened with} ...Nxd4 13. Nd5 $1 {with 
complications that will be covered later in this course.}) 12. Kb1 $1 {Improving 
White's king safety before committing to anything else. Many of Black's 
dangerous attacking options (checks on the c1-h6 diagonal, Black's thematic 
exchange sacrifice with ...Rxc3 with ...Qa5 (or ...Qc7) with ...Qxc3 doesn't 
threaten ...Qa1+ if White's king is on b1) are less powerful. Now Black has to 
make a commitment. Black doesn't have any waiting move that is as useful as 12. 
Kb1.} (12. h4 $6 h5 13. g4 hxg4 14. h5 Nxh5 15. Bh6 e6 16. Rdg1 Qf6 17. fxg4 
{would give White a winning initiative if it weren't for} 17... Bxh6 $1 18. Qxh6 
Qf4+ $1 {trading queens. This is why the White king would rather be on b1. It's 
also useful for other reasons, such as if Black plays the standard ...Rxc3 
sacrifice (after Bh6 and ...Bxh6 with Qxh6) followed by ...Qa5-xc3 (if the White 
king was on b1 there would not be a threat of ...Qa1+ with ...Qxd4+).}) Nc4 13. 
Bxc4 Rxc4 14. g4 {[%cal Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Bh5g6,Be3h6,Gd4e2][%csl Rg8] If Black's 
knight were still on e5, he would have the powerful resource ...b5! where White 
can't take on b5 without losing the f3 pawn, giving Black the initiative. Black 
now has a choice - be wiped off the board with a standard attack (h4-h5-xg6, 
Bh6-xg7 and Qh6 with Nd5) or play unsound sacrifices to fight for the 
initiative. Theory suggests option #2. White has better chances to fight for the 
initiative without sacrifices because ...g6 made weaknesses on the kingside and 
White doesn't have a corresponding weakness on the queenside. Below are some 
sub-variations on the unsound sacrifices that Black can try.} (14. g4 14... b5 
15. Ndxb5 {these complications are analyzed in more detail in the full course. 
Summary: White is up a pawn for no compensation if he is accurate.}) (14. g4 
14... b5 {White can play Negi's recommended 15.h4 with better chances in the 
resulting middlegame, or accept an unsound sacrifice with my recommended} 15. b3 
b4 $1 16. bxc4 bxc3 17. Qxc3 {. For more information on how White should 
consolidate his material advantage, see the full course.}) *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
