[SourceTitle "05 Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4705035"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian is one of Black's most dynamic options against 1. e4. 
Black controls the d4-square with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn, aiming to 
create an imbalance in pawn majorities if White plays d4.} 2. Nf3 {White 
develops and plans to open the center with d4 in order to exploit his lead in 
development.} d6 {2... d6 fights for control of the e5-square so that Black can 
play ...Nf6 without having to worry about e5 ideas.} 3. d4 {White opens the 
center in order to highlight his lead in development and to fight for the 
initiative.} cxd4 {Black trades his c-pawn for White's d-pawn, creating a 
central pawn majority.} 4. Nxd4 {White recaptures the pawn and establishes a 
strong knight on d4. Nxd4 is the most natural recapture as 4. Qxd4 would allow 
Black to develop and gain time on the queen with 4... Nc6.} Nf6 {Black develops 
with tempo. Delaying this move would allow White to increase his space advantage 
with c4 before playing Nc3, restricting Black's activity and preventing the 
...d5/...b5 breaks.} 5. Nc3 {White develops a piece and protects his d4-pawn. 5. 
Nc3 is superior to 5. Bd3 because it restricts Black from playing the ...d5 
break.} g6 {Black prepares to fianchetto his kingside bishop which would be very 
active on the open long diagonal. This signifies the Dragon Variation. The 
consequences of 5... g6 is that White now has a hook to open the h-file (h4-h5), 
increasing his prospects for a kingside attack.} 6. Be3 {White intends to 
rapidly develop (f3, Qd2, Bc4, O-O-O). After rapidly development, White would 
like to exchange dark-squared bishops (Bh6-xg7) in order to weaken the 
dark-squares near the Black king (h6, g7, h8) which can be exploited with 
White's queen and h1-rook after opening the h-file (h4-h5) . This plan is known 
as the Yugoslav attack. “'White's attack plays itself... weak players even 
beat Grandmasters with it.' - Bobby Fischer (Former World Champion, 
1972-1975)”} Bg7 (6... Ng4 7. Bb5+ $1 {White wins material because} 7... Bd7 
{loses a piece to} 8. Qxg4 {.}) 7. f3 {White prepares Qd2 by preventing ...Ng4.} 
O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 (8... d5 $6 9. e5 Nfd7 10. f4 {White has a space advantage and 
superior center control.}) 9. Bc4 {White prevents the ...d5 break and prepares 
to castle queenside.} Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 {This is a sharp position where 
both sides have clear plans. Black aims to attack White's queenside, where 
White's king is. Black usually plays ...Ne5-Nc4 to gain the bishop pair, and 
sometimes sacrifices the exchange with ...Rxc3 in order to expose White's 
queenside (if White's queen leaves d2 with a premature Bh6 and ...Bxh6). Black's 
queenside attack is helped by Black's fianchettoed bishop baring pressure down 
the queenside. White's plan is to open the h file (g4 with h4 and h5, or 
sometimes h4-h5 without g4 as a pawn sacrifice), trade dark squared bishops, and 
attack Black's kingside. White's plan is rather straightforward, so it can be 
very difficult to defend Black's position.} Nxd4 {Many Black players didn't like 
Black's chances in the 11...Ne5 12.Kb1! lines, where White is objectively 
better, so they tried to find earlier improvements. 11...Nxd4 (the Topalov 
Dragon) is the main alternative. Black aims to follow up with ...b5.} 12. Bxd4 
b5 13. Nd5 {As Black's queenside pawn storm was sped up by ...Nxd4, White 
changes plans. White aims to centralize all (Rh1 is optional) his pieces before 
committing to a kingside pawn storm.} (13. Bxa7 b4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Qa5 
{gives Black dangerous compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) Nxd5 14. Bxg7 
{White trades Black's most dangerous minor piece.} Kxg7 15. exd5 {This is a 
thematic pawn structure that can arise in some other lines with ...Nxd4. White 
has pressure down the e-file and powerful centralization. h4-h5 is still 
possible. If Black wants any counterplay, he should play fast, which involves a 
pawn sacrifice.} a5 {Black threatens 16... a4.} 16. a3 {[%cal 
Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Bh5g6,Bd2d4,Bh1e1][%csl Rg7] White creates a retreat square for Bb3. 
This is the main starting position of the Topalov Dragon. The onus is on Black 
to prove he knows his stuff because White's plan is easy: pry open the h-file 
(h4-h5) and possibly increase his center control with Qd4+ and Rhe1.} ({It's 
worth mentioning that after} 16. a3 16... b4 17. axb4 axb4 {I recommend} 18. h4 
{instead of 18. Qxb4 in order to increase the speed of White's kingside attack. 
Qxb4 is playable, but it opens lines on the queenside and Black will be able to 
generate counterplay using them.}) *

