[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4705038"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian is one of Black's most dynamic options against 1. e4. 
Black controls the d4-square with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn, aiming to 
create an imbalance in pawn majorities if White plays d4.} 2. Nf3 {White 
develops and plans to open the center with d4 in order to exploit his lead in 
development.} d6 {2... d6 fights for control of the e5-square so that Black can 
play ...Nf6 without having to worry about e5 ideas.} 3. d4 {White opens the 
center in order to highlight his lead in development and to fight for the 
initiative.} cxd4 {Black trades his c-pawn for White's d-pawn, creating a 
central pawn majority.} 4. Nxd4 {White recaptures the pawn and establishes a 
strong knight on d4. Nxd4 is the most natural recapture as 4. Qxd4 would allow 
Black to develop and gain time on the queen with 4... Nc6.} Nf6 {Black develops 
with tempo. Delaying this move would allow White to increase his space advantage 
with c4 before playing Nc3, restricting Black's activity and preventing the 
...d5/...b5 breaks.} 5. Nc3 {White develops a piece and protects his d4-pawn. 5. 
Nc3 is superior to 5. Bd3 because it restricts Black from playing the ...d5 
break.} Nc6 {The Classical Sicilian.} 6. Bc4 {White develops actively and 
prepares for a possible ...e5 by controling the d5-square.} (6. Be3 {isn't ideal 
due to} 6... Ng4 $1) e6 {Black blunts the c4-bishop and prepares to develop his 
queenside.} 7. Be3 {White's development plan is Qe2 with Bb3 and O-O-O. This 
plan is known as the Velimirovic Attack.} Be7 8. Qe2 a6 9. Bb3 Qc7 {Move 7-9 
alternatives don't stop White's development plan.} 10. O-O-O {[%cal 
Bh1g1,Bg2g4,Bg4g5][%csl Re8] White intends to fight for a kingside initiative 
with Rhg1 and g4-g5.} ({White generally wants to play Rhg1 before g4 to avoid 
...Nxd4 followed by ...e5 and ...Bxg4, but if Black moves his c6-knight White 
can play g4 without preparation. For example,} 10. O-O-O 10... Na5 11. g4 b5 12. 
g5 Nxb3+ (12... Nd7 $2 13. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 14. Nxe6 {with Nxg7+ and Nf5}) 13. axb3 
Nd7 14. Nf5 $1 ({the calm} 14. h4 {is also playable}) exf5 15. Nd5 Qd8 16. exf5 
{with a powerful initiative. For more information, see the full course.}) *

