1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian is one of Black's most dynamic options against 1. e4. 
Black controls the d4-square with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn, aiming to 
create an imbalance in pawn majorities if White plays d4.} 2. Nf3 {White 
develops and plans to open the center with d4 in order to exploit his lead in 
development.} d6 {2... d6 fights for control of the e5-square so that Black can 
play ...Nf6 without having to worry about e5 ideas.} 3. d4 {White opens the 
center in order to highlight his lead in development and to fight for the 
initiative.} cxd4 {Black trades his c-pawn for White's d-pawn, creating a 
central pawn majority.} 4. Nxd4 {White recaptures the pawn and establishes a 
strong knight on d4. Nxd4 is the most natural recapture as 4. Qxd4 would allow 
Black to develop and gain time on the queen with 4... Nc6.} Nf6 {Black develops 
with tempo. Delaying this move would allow White to increase his space advantage 
with c4 before playing Nc3, restricting Black's activity and preventing the 
...d5/...b5 breaks.} 5. Nc3 {White develops a piece and protects his d4-pawn. 5. 
Nc3 is superior to 5. Bd3 because it restricts Black from playing the ...d5 
break.} a6 {The Najdorf. Black makes a useful waiting move by controlling the 
b5-square, preventing Bb5+ and preparing ...b5. Black can choose his system of 
development depending on how White responds.} 6. Bc4 {6. Bc4 is known as the 
Fischer-Sozin Attack and is one of the most aggressive ways of playing against 
the Najdorf. White wants to develop his pieces rapidly and can castle either 
direction. White also restricts Black from playing the ...e5 because White would 
have additional control over the weak d5-square.} e6 {Black blunts the c4-bishop 
and prepares to develop his kingside.} (6... e5 $6 {allows} 7. Nf5 {where White 
has excellent control over the weak light squares.}) 7. Bb3 {The most flexible 
move. Since Black will attack the bishop with ...b5 or ...Qc7 anyways, White 
retreats. 7. O-O isn't as flexible because White shouldn't commit to castling 
kingside. In some cases, White will play g4-g5 followed by castling queenside 
and a kingside pawn storm.} b5 {Black gains queenside space and prepares to play 
...Bb7.} 8. O-O Be7 {It's too risky for Black to grab the e4-pawn.} (8... b4 9. 
Na4 Nxe4 {White has more than enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn and 
can use his lead in development to create concrete threats. For example,} 10. 
Re1 d5 11. Bf4 Be7 12. Nf5 $1 exf5 13. Qxd5 {White wins the sacrificed material 
back while keeping the initiative.}) 9. Qf3 {White brings his queen closer to 
the kingside (this is where White wants to attack) and threatens to win material 
with e5.} Qc7 (9... Qb6 10. Be3 Qb7 11. Qg3 {White will play} f3 {with a slight 
advantage due to his superior center control.}) (9... O-O $2 10. e5 dxe5 11. 
Nxe6 $1 {followed by} Qxa8 {.}) 10. Qg3 {White threatens Qxg7.} O-O 11. Bh6 
{Threatening Qxg7#.} Ne8 12. Rad1 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gc3e2,Ge2f4,Gf4h5,Bd4f3][%csl 
Rg7] White has the initiative due to his lead in development. White should 
follow up with Nf3 intending a kingside attack (Ne2-f4-h5) or a central break 
(Bf4 with e5). For a model game in this variation, see *Garry Kasparov vs. Boris 
Gelfand*.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Sidelines"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the"]
[Black "Alekhine (4...Bg4)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "06 Sidelines"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4708230"]

1. e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine Defense is a hypermodern way for Black to play. Black 
provokes White into creating a large center in hope of undermining it later on.} 
2. e5 {White gains space and attacks the f6-knight.} Nd5 {Black centralizes his 
knight.} 3. d4 {White places another pawn in the center.} d6 {Black begins to 
undermine White's central pawn mass.} 4. Nf3 {White develops a piece and 
supports his e5-pawn. White could choose to be really aggressive by playing 4. 
c4 Nb6 5. f4, but this approach is risky because Black will have a lead in 
development. 4. Nf3 gives White the advantage without much risk.} Bg4 {Black 
pins White's f3-knight.} 5. Be2 {“'This was the old main line, but interest 
has waned because White has a convincing route to an edge everywhere.' - GM John 
Shaw ” White's plan is to rapidly develop his pieces followed by gaining space 
with c4. Black has less space and White has easier development, so White can get 
an advantage with normal moves.} e6 6. O-O {6. h3 and 6. c4 are also strong, but 
less flexible.} Be7 7. c4 {White gains space and attacks Black's d5-knight.} Nb6 
8. Nc3 {White has a better position due to his lead in development and space 
advantage.} O-O (8... dxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Qxd4 11. Rd1 {White will play 
Nb5 with a powerful initiative worth more than the sacrificed pawn.}) 9. Be3 
{White has excellent development and is ready to open the center with exd6 
followed by d5.} Nc6 (9... N8d7 10. exd6 cxd6 11. b3) 10. exd6 {White prepares 
to play d5 without allowing Black to take on e5.} cxd6 11. d5 {White seizes 
central space with gain of time.} exd5 (11... Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Ne5 13. dxe6 {White 
opens the position to take advantage of his superior piece activity and has the 
initiative. For example,} 13... Nxf3+ (13... fxe6 14. Bg4) 14. Qxf3 fxe6 15. 
Qe4) 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 {[%cal Bf1d1,Bh2h3][%csl Rd6] White's position is 
slightly better due to his excellent centralization and Black's isolated 
d-pawn.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Sidelines"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to the"]
[Black "Alekhine (4...dxe5)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "06 Sidelines"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4708231"]

1. e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine Defense is a hypermodern way for Black to play. Black 
provokes White into creating a large center in hope of undermining it later on.} 
2. e5 {White gains space and attacks the f6-knight.} Nd5 {Black centralizes his 
knight.} 3. d4 {White places another pawn in the center.} d6 {Black begins to 
undermine White's central pawn mass.} 4. Nf3 {White develops a piece and 
supports his e5-pawn. White could choose to be really aggressive by playing 4. 
c4 Nb6 5. f4, but this approach is risky because Black will have a lead in 
development. 4. Nf3 gives White the advantage without much risk.} dxe5 {Black 
releases the central tension in order to reduce White's space advantage.} 5. 
Nxe5 c6 (5... Nd7 {can be met by the safe 6.Nf3 or the sharp} 6. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 7. 
Qh5+ Ke6 8. c4 {. I recommend the sharp option. For more information, see the 
full course.}) 6. Be2 Bf5 7. O-O {[%cal Bc2c4,Bb1c3,Bc1e3,Gb8d7,Ge5f3][%csl Rd5] 
White is slightly better due to his space advantage and smooth development. 
White plans to rapidly develop (c4, Nc3, Be3) and squeeze Black. ...Nd7 should 
be met with Nf3 in order to avoid trades (the side who has less space generally 
wants to trade to free his position). For a model game in this variation, see 
Viswanathan Anand vs. Hikaru Nakamura (Blitz, 2016).} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Sidelines"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
