[White "Introduction to the"]
[Black "Alekhine (4...g6)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "06 Sidelines"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4708232"]

1. e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine Defense is a hypermodern way for Black to play. Black 
provokes White into creating a large center in hope of undermining it later on.} 
2. e5 {White gains space and attacks the f6-knight.} Nd5 {Black centralizes his 
knight.} 3. d4 {White places another pawn in the center.} d6 {Black begins to 
undermine White's central pawn mass.} 4. Nf3 {White develops a piece and 
supports his e5-pawn. White could choose to be really aggressive by playing 4. 
c4 Nb6 5. f4, but this approach is risky because Black will have a lead in 
development. 4. Nf3 gives White the advantage without much risk.} g6 {Black 
prepares to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop.} 5. Bc4 {5. Bc4 is more 
favorable in the 4... g6 lines than the 4... Bg4 lines because Black isn't able 
to play ...e6 here without weakening the f6-square.} Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 {The most 
consistant follow up to 4... g6.} (6... a5 7. a4) (6... Nc6 7. a4 a5 8. exd6 
cxd6 9. d5) 7. a4 {White threatens to play a5.} a5 {The inclusion of a4 and 
...a5 favors White because White would have more potential to use the weakened 
b5-square than Black would have to use the b4-square.} 8. Ng5 {White targets 
Black's f7-pawn and prepares to gain space with f4.} e6 {Black decides to weaken 
his kingside dark-squares in order to protect his f7-pawn and prevent White from 
playing e6.} (8... d5 9. f4) 9. f4 {White supports his e5-pawn.} dxe5 {Black 
exchanges on e5 in order to open the d-file, offering him some counterplay 
against White's d4-pawn.} (9... O-O 10. O-O {Black should take on} e5 {now (or 
soon) because he will have a passive position if he is unable to target White's 
d4-pawn.}) 10. fxe5 {White opens the f-file.} c5 {Black challenges White's pawn 
center.} (10... O-O 11. O-O c5 12. c3 {doesn't change much and is likely to 
transpose.}) 11. c3 {White supports his d4-pawn.} cxd4 12. O-O {White castles 
and attacks Black's f7-pawn.} (12. cxd4 {is also playable and is likely to 
transpose.}) O-O (12... dxc3 {loses to} 13. Qxd8+ Kxd8 14. Nxf7+) 13. cxd4 Nc6 
14. Nf3 {White has a strong center and intends on fighting for a kingside 
initiative with Nc3-e4 and Bg5. To obtain counterplay, Black will need to attack 
White's center with ...f6.} f6 15. Nc3 (15. exf6 Qxf6 16. Be3 Nd5 17. Bf2 Nf4 
{gives Black counterplay.}) fxe5 16. Bg5 {White is more focused on initiative 
than material. His pieces are more prepared for the opening of the position, 
this is more important than a pawn.} Qd7 (16... Bf6 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. dxe5) 17. 
dxe5 {White opens the center. Black is able to win White's e5-pawn, remaining a 
pawn ahead, but White would have excellent compensation (even in the endgame) 
due to his excellent piece activity, Black's weak e6-pawn, and Black's lack of 
queenside development.} Nxe5 (17... Qxd1 {White can take back with either rook 
and has more than enough compensation for his sacrificed pawn due to his 
superior piece activity and lead in development.}) 18. Nxe5 Rxf1+ ({Black can 
play} 18... Qxd1 {, but he would be resigning himself to a long defense. White 
would have a better endgame due to his superior piece activity, Black's isolated 
e-pawn, and Black's undeveloped queenside. Black's extra pawn is the only thing 
preventing him from being completely lost. White can recapture the queen with 
either rook.}) 19. Qxf1 Qd4+ (19... Bxe5 20. Rd1 {gives White a powerful 
initiative.}) 20. Kh1 Qxe5 21. Bd8 {[%cal Ba1d1,Bd1e1,Bd8b6][%csl 
Gf1,Gc3,Gb3,Ga1,Gd8,Rb6,Re5] The key move! White attacks Black's b6-knight with 
tempo (he didn't have to retreat his bishop) and has a decisive initiative due 
to his superior piece activity and Black's exposed king.} (21. Bd8 21... Ra6 22. 
Rd1) (21. Bd8 21... Qc5 22. Ne4 Qc6 23. Ng5) (21. Bd8 21... Nd5 22. Nxd5 exd5 
23. Re1) *

