1. e4 Nc6 {1... Nc6 is more of a move-order trick than anything else. The main 
idea is that the game will become sharp after 2. d4 e5! Therefore, it is a good 
practical choice to simply continue development with 2. Nf3, there is no need to 
prepare sharp forcing lines against such a rare sideline.} 2. Nf3 {White invites 
a transposition into a Pirc or King's Pawn Game.} (2. Nf3 2... e5 3. Bb5 
{transposes into the Ruy Lopez.}) (2. Nf3 2... e6 3. d4 {gives White a nice 
French defense where the c6-knight is misplaced.}) (2. Nf3 2... d6 3. d4 {gives 
White positions similar to in the Pirc. White has a space advantage and smooth 
development, the c6-knight gives White the possibility of playing d5 with 
tempo.}) *

