1. e4 g6 {Black concedes the center. At GM level, Black tends to do this in 
order to counter-attack it later, but many club players who play this don't 
understand how to receive compensation for White's pawn center. 1... d6 tends to 
lead to similar positions.} 2. d4 {White occupies the center with his pawns.} 
Bg7 {Black continues with his fianchetto plan on the kingside.} 3. Nc3 {White 
develops and supports his e4-pawn.} d6 {Black plays ...d6 to support the 
e5-square.} 4. f4 {[%cal Bg1f3,Bf1d3,Be4e5,Be1g1,Bh1f1][%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4] White 
gains space and plans to play Nf3 followed by Bd3 and e5 to fight for a 
central/kingside initiative.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
