[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4708237"]

1. e4 d5 {Black's direct strike in the center is known as the Scandinavian 
Defense. The downside of this move is that Black's queen is drawn out quite 
early on, which can hand White the initiative.} 2. exd5 {White captures the 
pawn, drawing out Black's queen from d8.} Qxd5 {Black recaptures the pawn. 2... 
Nf6 is also possible, but White still gets excellent center control after 3. d4. 
“'This is the real Scandinavian, it also makes sense to me, strategically, as 
the pawn is taken straight away and White will have to put the knight on the 
awkward c3-square to gain the tempo as he does with c2-c4 against the knight in 
the 2... Nf6 line. Of course, the awkwardness of the c3-knight is that it blocks 
the space-gaining c4-advance.' - GM John Shaw”} 3. Nc3 {White develops with 
gain of tempo.} Qd8 {Black retreats his queen. 3... Qd8 is less active than 3... 
Qd6 or 3... Qa5, but at least White isn't currently able to attack Black's 
queen. The downside of this approach is that ...Qxd5-d8 cost Black 2 tempi, 
White can count on an advantage due to his lead in development.} 4. d4 {White 
gains central space and prevents ...e5.} Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 {isn't as strong due 
to} 5... a6 $1 {where Black will play ...b5 and ...c5 with counterplay.}) Bg4 
{Black pins White's f3-knight and applies pressure on White's center.} (5... Bf5 
6. Ne5 {followed by} g4 {or Qf3 gives White a powerful initiative.}) 6. h3 Bxf3 
{“'The reason for ...Bg4 and ...Bxf3 in the main line is two-fold. First, if 
the bishop instead develops to the f5 square, White can often gain an initiative 
by Bc4, Ne5, g4, and h4. This kingside pawn storm is the reason why Black can't 
bank on ...Bh5 in response to h3, too. It's a dangerous plan, and I don't think 
Black has a reasonable way to counter it.' - IM John Bartholomew”} 7. Qxf3 
{White develops his queen and attacks Black's b7-pawn.} c6 {Black controls the 
d5-square and prevents Qxb7.} 8. Bf4 {White develops his dark-squared bishop to 
an active square and prepares to castle queenside. Black can try to punish this 
move with ...Qxd4, but taking the d4-pawn is very risky with White's lead in 
development and leads to an advantage for White with best play. It was not known 
until recently that White can safely allow Black to capture on d4, that is most 
likely why the main line is 8. Be3. “'I like this move the best, it is most 
active, and I think it leads to an advantage in a direct line.' - GM John Shaw 
” “'A relatively new try that was recommended by GM John Shaw in his book 
'Playing 1. e4 - Caro-Kann, e5 & Minor Lines.' White posts the dark-square 
bishop actively and dares Black to capture on d4.' - IM John Bartholomew”} e6 
(8... Qxd4 $2 9. Nb5 $1 cxb5 10. Bxb5+ Nbd7 11. Qxb7 Rd8 12. Bc7 {gives White a 
significant advantage, one sample continuation could be} 12... Qe4+ 13. Qxe4 
Nxe4 14. O-O-O {.}) 9. O-O-O {White is slightly better due to his lead in 
development, bishop pair, and space advantage. IM John Bartholomew recommends 
this position for Black in his Chessable repertoire, so it is worth learning how 
to keep the advantage against his recommendation.} Bb4 {John Bartholomew's 
recommendation. Black prepares ...Bxc3, intending to meet Qxc3 with ...Nd5, in 
order to force White to give up the bishop pair.} 10. Kb1 {White improves his 
king position and prepares to play g4 by defending his a2-pawn.} (10. g4 {isn't 
ideal due to} 10... Bxc3 {where} 11. Qxc3 {loses material to} 11... Qd5 {due to 
the fork on White's h1-rook and a2-pawn.}) Bxc3 {The standard follow up to 
...Bb4. Black aims to meet Qxc3 with ...Nd5 and ...Nxf4, forcing White to lose 
his bishop pair. Against other moves, White can also start a kingside pawn storm 
with g4-g5 and finish his development with Bg2 or Be2.} 11. Qxc3 Nd5 {If Black 
does not play this, White will be able to keep his bishop pair and Black will 
not have compensation.} 12. Qg3 Nxf4 13. Qxf4 Nd7 {“'White has additional 
space plus a bishop versus a knight, but Black's prospects look reasonable to 
me. After a move like ...Qd8-f6 he should look to castle queenside.' - IM John 
Bartholomew”} 14. g4 {[%cal 
Bf1e2,Bf1g2,Bh3h4,Bg4g5,Bh4h5,Bc2c4,Bd4d5,Gd8f6,Gf4e3,Gf4c7] White gains space 
and prepares a kingside pawn storm. He intends on finishing his development with 
Bg2 (more active than Be2 and prepares d5) or Be2 (c4 is more plausible if Black 
plays ...Nb6) and can eventually open the center with c4 and d5. “'White has 
more space and a bishop against a knight. There is no way for Black to claim 
equality, so he will have to suffer for a long time.' - GM John Shaw ”} (14. 
g4 14... Nb6 15. c4) (14. g4 14... Qe7 15. c4) (14. g4 14... Qf6 {can be met 
with the safe 15.Qe3 or the aggressive 15.Qc7. If White plays 15.Qe3, he can 
fight for a long-term initiative with Be2/Bg2, a kingside pawn storm, and 
possibly c4 and d5. If White plays} 15. Qc7 {, White will almost certainly win 
both Black's b7-pawn and c6-pawn as defending the b7-pawn with} 15... Rb8 
{allows White to open the center with} 16. d5 {(this is too dangerous to allow 
when Black hasn't yet castled), where Black has some, but not full, compensation 
for the sacrificed material. In both the long-term initiative plan with 15.Qe3 
and the immediate assault with 15.Qc7, White has the advantage.}) *

