1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 {“'The idea is basically to avoid opening 
theory while keeping a solid structure. By limiting the confrontation between 
the two armies, there is a lot to play for.' - GM John Shaw”} 4. d4 Nf6 {The 
most flexible move.} (4... c6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 (6... Bh5 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 
{White will play} Bf4 {and h4-h5 with a powerful initiative.}) 7. Qxf3 {White 
has the bishop pair and the initiative.} 7... Qxd4 8. Bf4 $1 Nf6 9. Nb5 $1 
{transposed into a refuted variation of the} 3...Qd8 {variation.}) 5. Nf3 a6 
{Black prevents Nb5 and prepares to play ...b5.} (5... c6 6. Ne5 Nbd7 7. Nc4 Qc7 
8. Qf3 Nb6 9. Bf4 {White has the advantage because of his lead in development.}) 
6. g3 {White fianchettos his light-squared bishop. Other than g2 being a good 
square for White's bishop, fianchettoing especially makes sense because Black 
had intended on playing ...b5, and White wants to beat Black to the 
long-diagonal.} Bg4 {Black develops his bishop and pins White's f3-knight. The 
downside of this approach is that a later h3 will force Black to lose time 
retreating his bishop (and allow an initiative with g4 and Ne5), while capturing 
on f3 would give up the bishop pair.} 7. Bg2 {White develops his bishop and 
occupies the long-diagonal.} Nc6 {Black prepares to castle queenside. Other 
approaches are too passive, they allow White to obtain the initiative without a 
fight (White can play natural developing moves and force matters with Bf4 and 
h3).} 8. O-O O-O-O 9. d5 {White gains space and begins forcing play. The 
resulting complications favor White due to his superior piece activity.} Ne5 
{Black centralizes his knight and prepares to trade on f3.} 10. Bf4 Nxf3+ (10... 
Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 {transposes.}) 11. Bxf3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 {[%cal 
Ge7e5,Gd5e6,Bf1e1,Ba1d1][%csl Rd6] White has the initiative due to his lead in 
development.} (12. Qxf3 12... e5 13. dxe6 Qxe6 {White can follow up with Bg5 and 
Rfe1.}) *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Model games"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Petroff: Judit Polgar"]
[Black "Anatoly Karpov"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SourceTitle "07 Model games"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4708276"]

{This game was played in 2003. Judit Polgar was the strongest woman in the 
world, rated over 2700 FIDE. Anatoly Karpov was a former world champion.} 1. e4 
e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Be7 {Black has a solid 
position, but White has some initiative due to her lead in development.} 7. O-O 
Nc6 {The main move and Black's most aggressive try. Black applies pressure on 
White's d4 pawn and can meet 8.c4 with ...Nb4. Alternatives will be discussed in 
the theory chapter.} 8. c4 {White tries to open the center to exploit her lead 
in development.} Nb4 9. Be2 {White keeps her bishop pair.} O-O 10. a3 {Black's 
knight must retreat. White can play Bd3 again later if she needs to.} Nc6 11. 
cxd5 {Opening the center.} Qxd5 12. Nc3 {Forcing Black to improve White's center 
control.} Nxc3 (12... Qf5 13. Bd3 {forces} ...Nxc3 {in circumstances that are 
more favorable for White due to the lost time moving Black's queen.}) 13. bxc3 
Qd6 {Black delays development for only one move, but this gives White a powerful 
initiative. Black's idea was to prevent c4 from coming with tempo.} (13... Bf5 
{is stronger, but White still has the initiative after} 14. c4 Qd6 15. d5 Ne5 
16. Nd4) 14. Rb1 {White develops a piece and hinders Bc8 developing, it is now 
stuck defending the b7 pawn. To develop Bc8, Black has to lose a tempo on ...b6 
or ...Rb8.} b6 15. Re1 {White develops another piece.} Be6 16. Bd3 {White can 
keep improving her pieces. Black doesn't have a good plan, while White has good 
prospects of a kingside attack due to her pawn center and piece coordination.} 
Rae8 17. Rb5 $1 {White prepares a rook-lift to the kingside.} Na5 {Black's 
knight aims for the weak c4-square. This is the only counterplay he can get. If 
Black waited instead, White could have built up a powerful initiative with c4 
(threatening d5) followed by Rh5 (threatening to take on h7), d5, and Bb2.} 18. 
Rbe5 {White has a powerful position in the center and Black's pieces are very 
passively placed. White intends to attack on the kingside after she finishes her 
development.} Nc6 (18... Nc4 19. Rxe6 fxe6 20. Bxc4) 19. R5e2 Bd7 20. d5 $1 
{White strikes in the center! Black can't take on d5 for tactical reasons.} Na5 
(20... Qxd5 21. Bxh7+ Kxh7 22. Qxd5) 21. Ne5 {White centralizes her knight, 
taking advantage of Nc6's absence.} Bf6 22. Bf4 Bxe5 23. Bxe5 {White's pieces 
are all coordinated and White's bishop pair is aiming towards the kingside. 
Black can win the a3 pawn, but this doesn't help him defend the kingside.} Qxa3 
24. Re3 {[%cal Bd1h5,Be3g3,Bd3h7,Be5g7][%csl Rg7,Rh7,Ge5,Gd3] White prepares 
Qh5.} Qc5 25. Bxh7+ $1 {A thematic bishop sacrifice to open the kingside.} Kxh7 
26. Qh5+ {Black resigns.} ({White has forced checkmate:} 26. Qh5+ 26... Kg8 27. 
Bxg7 Kxg7 28. Rg3+ Kf6 29. Qg5#) 1-0

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Model games"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ruy Lopez (Zaitsev): Viswanathan Anand"]
[Black "Rustam Kasimdzhanov"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SourceTitle "07 Model games"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4708277"]

{This game was played 2007 at the Chess Classic (Rapid Prelim). Black was a 
strong GM, but White would go on to become World Champion before 2007 ended.} 1. 
e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 
9. h3 Re8 {Black makes a flexible move that is useful in almost all of the 
Closed Ruy Lopez systems. Black aims to redevelop his kingside bishop (...Bf8, 
...g6, ...Bg7).} 10. d4 Bb7 {Black has transposed into the Zaitsev Variation, 
which is usually reached by the 9...Bb7 move order. Black is aiming for pressure 
on the e4 pawn. The Zaitsev is similar to the Breyer but allows both sides 
additional options: Black has the option of playing ...Na5 instead of ...Nb8, 
but if White chooses to play d4-d5 before Nc6 moves out of the way, White gains 
a tempo.} 11. Nbd2 Bf8 {One of the main benefits of the Zaitsev is that it 
interrupts White's thematic knight maneuver Nbd2-f1-g3.} 12. d5 (12. Nf1 {loses 
a pawn to} 12... exd4 {followed by ...Nxe4.}) {White prevents Black from opening 
the e-file in order to continue with his knight maneuver. White also gains a 
tempo on Nc6.} Nb8 (12... Na5 13. Bc2 {followed by 14.b4 forces Black to play 
...Nc4. After Nxc4 and ...bxc4, Black's c4 pawn would be very weak and can be 
targeted.}) 13. Nf1 {This pawn structure is thematic in the Zaitsev. Black's 
main attempt to fight for counterplay is his pawn break ...c6. After dxc6 
...Bxc6, Black's d5 square is weak but Black can try to advance ...d5 to free 
his pieces. The main fight in this variation of the Zaitsev revolves around the 
d5 square.} Nbd7 14. N3h2 {[%cal Bh2g4,Bg4f6,Bc1g5,Bg5f6][%csl Rf6,Gd5] White 
starts a thematic and deep strategic plan. White's plan is to trade Nh2 and Bc1 
for both of Black's knights (Bg5-xf6, Ng4-xf6+). This helps control the d5 
square because Black's knights are often one of Black's main fighters for d5. 
Then, after Black plays ...c6 (Black has no other method of obtaining 
counterplay. If Black doesn't play ...c6, White can fight for a kingside attack 
and/or try to create weaknesses on the queenside), White will try to exchange 
light squared bishops on d5, leaving him with a good knight (which has the d5 
outpost) against Black's passive dark-squared bishop. If this plan is completed 
without Black getting compensation or counterplay, White's position will be 
strategically won. A similar plan (trading all of the minor pieces except for 
White's good knight with the d5 outpost against Black's passive dark-squared 
bishop which is restricted by it's pawn structure) is attempted in some 
variations of the Najdorf because the pawn structure with ...c6 dxc6 is similar 
to the pawn structure Black has in the Najdorf when he plays ...e5.} Nc5 (14... 
h6 {is sometimes employed, preventing Bg5. The downside of} ...h6 {is that it is 
slow. This gives White enough time to fight for a kingside initiative with} 15. 
Ng4 {and will be dealt with in the theory chapter.}) 15. Bc2 c6 {Black 
challenges White's center.} 16. b4 {White gains a tempo forcing Nc5 to retreat 
before taking on c6. If White took on c6 first, Black would have more pressure 
on White's e4 pawn.} Ncd7 17. dxc6 {White creates the pawn structure that he was 
preparing for with his 14th move.} Bxc6 18. Bg5 {[%cal Bg5f6,Bh2g4,Bg4f6][%csl 
Gd5,Rf6]} h6 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 20. Ng4 Nxg4 21. Qxg4 {[%cal Bc2b3,Bf1e3,Ba1d1][%csl 
Gd5] White has completed phase 1 of his plan: trade Bc1 and Nh2 for Black's 
knights.} Bd7 (21... d5 {opens the center, but in White's favor:} 22. exd5 Qxd5 
23. Bb3 {gives White the initiative. White was more prepared for the opening of 
the center because his pieces were placed more aggressively. (Michael Adams vs. 
Ruslan Ponomariov 2002)}) 22. Qf3 Rc8 23. Bb3 {White continues fighting for the 
d5 square.} Be6 24. Rec1 {Ne3 was temporarily prevented due to ...Rxc3, so White 
takes a moment to defend his c3 pawn.} (24. Qd3 {also prepares} Ne3) Be7 25. Rc2 
{White prepares to play Rad1.} a5 26. Qd3 {White prepares to meet ...a4 with 
Bd5. If Black takes on d5, White can take back with his queen, maintaining the 
d5 outpost. If White wins the d5-square without making a concession, Black will 
have no compensation for White's superior minor piece, giving White a 
strategically won position.} Bxb3 {Black starts a combination to either win a 
pawn or be able to free his position with ...d5. If he did not go for this, he 
would be very passive and d5 would be a clear weakness.} 27. axb3 axb4 {[%cal 
Bf1e3,Be3d5][%csl Gd5,Re7]} 28. Ne3 $1 {White sacrifices a pawn to achieve his 
goal: a powerful knight on d5 against Black's inactive dark-squared bishop.} 
(28. cxb4 Rxc2 $1 {Black deflects White's queen from defending the d5 square.} 
29. Qxc2 d5 $1 {and Black has freed his position.}) bxc3 29. Rxc3 Rxc3 30. Qxc3 
Bg5 31. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5,Rg5] Black's extra pawn is blockaded, rendering it almost 
useless. White aims to use his superior piece activity and powerful knight to 
target Black's b5 pawn. If White wins Black's b5 pawn, Black will have no 
compensation for White's superior minor piece, giving White a strategically won 
position.} Qd7 32. Ra6 {White prepares to dominate the c-file with Rc6 or target 
Black's b6 pawn with Rb6.} Rc8 {Black prevents Rc6.} 33. Qd3 Kh7 34. Kh2 {Both 
sides take a moment to improve their king safety.} Rc1 35. g3 {White can keep 
strengthening his position. His advantage is long-term, it isn't going to run 
away if White plays slowly.} Bd8 36. Kg2 Rc8 37. h4 {White can keep improving, 
Black can only wait.} Rc5 38. Ne3 {White decided that he has strengthened his 
position enough. He is ready to provoke concrete action.} Be7 (38... Rc6 
{allows} 39. Qxb5 {. Note that Qxb5 would not work if White's king were still on 
the first rank due to} 39... Rc1+ {. If your opponent is helpless, it is often 
good to improve your position to the utmost before provoking complications.}) 
39. b4 {Black can't safely keep his material advantage.} Rc8 (39... Rc7 40. Qd5 
{attacking Black's f7 pawn} 40... Bf8 41. Rb6) 40. Rb6 {[%cal Bb6b5,Bd3b5][%csl 
Rb5]} g6 41. Qxb5 {White's knight is far stronger than Black's bishop and White 
has an outside passed pawn. Black's d6 pawn is basically useless because it can 
be blockaded by Nd5. White's position is won.} Qxb5 42. Rxb5 Bd8 43. Rb7 Kg7 44. 
Nd5 Rc4 45. Rd7 {Black resigns. If Black had played on, he would have lost his 
d6 pawn and White's passed b-pawn would be too powerful for Black to hope for a 
draw.} 1-0

