{This game was played in the World FIDE Championship (2004) between 2 strong 
GMs. White was rated 2645 and Black was rated 2698.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 
dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. g3 b6 {While Black has alternatives to the ...c5-xd4 endgame 
if he plays 5...Ngf6, but one of his best attempts to equalize is to fight for 
the long-diagonal. If White prevents Black from fianchettoing his light-squared 
bishop, it will likely remain passive for a long time (or Black will have to 
make a concession to free it). Therefore, 5...b6 (aiming to fianchetto Black's 
bishop) is one of his most logical approaches.} 6. Bg2 Rb8 {Black needs to 
prepare ...Bb7 by adding support the b7-square, otherwise White could have 
discovered attacks to win the bishop.} (6... Bb7 7. Nf6+ Ngxf6 8. Bxb7 {White is 
better due to his bishop pair.}) 7. Nf3 {White is developing his pieces 
harmoniously.} Bb7 8. Qe2 {White protects his e4-knight and develops his queen.} 
Ngf6 9. Nxf6+ {When you have a space advantage, it is usually better to not 
trade pieces as to not help uncramp your opponent. In this case, it is fine 
because White is only trading one pair of minor pieces and retreating would lose 
a tempo, which would be a bigger concession.} Nxf6 10. O-O {White has excellent 
piece coordination and center control. Black has activated his problem piece 
(his light-squared bishop) and has a solid position, but due to White's lead in 
development and excellent center control, he can fight for the advantage without 
risk.} Be7 11. Rd1 {White develops his rook. Rd1 makes sense because it impedes 
...c5 (which can now be met by dxc5 with a discovered attack on Black's queen) 
as well as doesn't commit how White will develop his queenside. White can choose 
to either fianchetto his dark-squared bishop or play Bf4.} O-O 12. c4 {[%cal 
Bb2b3,Bc1b2,Bc1f4][%csl Gc4,Gd4] White gains space and is slowly improving his 
position.} Nd7 {12...Qe8 is a logical alternative. Either way, White has a space 
advantage and has the choice of how he would like to develop his queenside.} 13. 
Bf4 {13.b3 with 14.Bb2 is also a logical option. 13.Bf4 is more active but 
allows Black to trade at least one pair of minor pieces. Since White's remaining 
pieces will be more active than Black's, White will still have some advantage.} 
Bd6 14. Ne5 {Exchanging on d6 only helps Black control the center, allowing 
Black to capture on f4 allows Black to double White's f-pawns.} Bxg2 15. Kxg2 
{[%cal Ge5c6][%csl Ra6,Rb7,Rc6] Black has solved the problem of his worst minor 
piece, but now has weak light-squares on the queenside. White is now threatening 
Nc6, winning the exchange.} Bxe5 16. dxe5 {[%cal Gd1d8][%csl Rd8,Rd7] Though Bf4 
is currently passively placed, it is still better not to trade it, because White 
has more space. Black's d7-knight is now tied down on the d-file, which White 
can quickly take over (Rd2 with Rad1). Other than doubling rooks on the d-file, 
White can try to take over Black's weak queenside light-squares with Qe4-c6.} 
Qe7 17. Rd2 {[%cal Ba1d1,Be2e4,Be2g4][%csl Rd7] Simple play. White doubles rooks 
on the d-file.} Rfd8 18. Qg4 {[%cal Ba1d1,Gd1d8,Bf4g5,Bg5h6,Gg4g8][%csl 
Rg8,Rd7,Rd8,Rg7] White begins a kingside attack. Other than an aggressive move, 
18.Qg4 is also prophylaxis: Black's main weakness is Nd7 being tied down. Black 
had intended to play either ...Nf8 or ...Nc5, now either of those moves loses to 
Bg5 with a skewer. Black's knight needs to stay put in order to guard the 
f6-square, giving White the time to increase the pressure.} Qe8 {Black prepares 
to play ...Nf8, since Bg5 is no longer skewering his queen.} 19. Bh6 {[%cal 
Gg4g7,Gh6g7][%csl Rg7] White doesn't give Black a moment's respite and forces 
him to weaken his dark-squares with ...g6 due to his threat of Qxg7#.} g6 (19... 
Qf8 20. Rad1 {White wins material because Black can't retreat his knight, 
Black's queen isn't really defending Rd8 because it is overloaded, also 
defending against Qxg7#.}) 20. Qf4 {[%cal Bh6g5,Bg5f6][%csl Ge5,Rf6] White 
consolidates his advantage by protecting his e5-pawn. Now Black's d7-knight is 
tied down in a different way: it is defending the f6-square in case White 
decides to increase his kingside initiative with Bg5-f6.} f6 {White's threat of 
dark-square domination with Bg5-f6 (with a kingside attack, such as h4-h5-xg6 
with Qh6 and an attack on the h-file) was too powerful to ignore. Black had to 
play ...f6 before White placed his bishop there.} 21. exf6 e5 {Black's only hope 
of counterplay is to strike back in the center. Objectively, it isn't enough.} 
22. f7+ {White gives back the pawn to force a favorable endgame.} Qxf7 23. Qxf7+ 
Kxf7 24. Rad1 {[%cal Gd1d8,Bh6g5,Gg5d8][%csl Rd7,Rd8] Black's passive d7-knight 
gives him a losing position. Black is unable to move his knight because it is 
pinned (...Nf6 loses to Rxd8). White is now threatening to remove the defender 
with Bg5.} Ke6 25. Bg5 a5 {Black sacrifices the exchange. White knows that he 
can win the exchange (with a won position) at any time, but since Black can't 
safely move his knight or d8-rook without losing even more material, White can 
afford to improve his position to the maximum before grabbing the material 
advantage, especially since Black can't do much but wait in the meantime.} 26. 
a4 {White gains space and restricts Black's queenside pawns.} Ra8 27. f4 {White 
gains space. Black can't safely take on f4 because his king will be too exposed 
on the open e-file.} h6 28. Bxd8 {Finally, White accepts the offered exchange.} 
Rxd8 29. fxe5 {White is now up the exchange and a pawn.} Ke7 {Black can't 
capture on e5 because his d7-knight would fall.} 30. g4 {The win for White is 
now a matter of technique.} Ke6 31. h4 Ke7 32. e6 Kxe6 33. Re2+ Kf7 34. Rf1+ Kg8 
35. Rd2 {Black resigns. White intended on playing Rfd1 next and Black is unable 
to save his d7-knight.} 1-0

