1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 {Black strikes at the base of White's pawn chain and 
provokes the opening of the position.} 4. dxc5 {White is happy to open the 
position since he has easier development.} e6 (4... Nc6 5. a3 e6 {was played in 
the game, but the game soon transposed into this repertoire's recommended 
line.}) 5. a3 {[%cal Bb2b4]} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5][%csl Re5]} 6. Nf3 {[%csl Ge5]} 
Bxc5 7. b4 Bb6 8. Bb2 Nge7 9. Bd3 Ng6 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 a5 {11...f6 is more 
accurate. Black should be challenging White's center.} 12. b5 Nce7 13. a4 {White 
supports his b5-pawn.} ({13.g3 is slightly more accurate because if Black 
challenges White's center with ...f6 then g3 is a more accurate waiting move to 
prevent ...Nf4.}) Bc5 {Too slow. Black should challenge White's center.} (13... 
f6 {is stronger but after} 14. exf6 gxf6 15. c4 Nf4 16. Bf1 {White is slightly 
better, though} g3 {would have been a better waiting move than a4.}) 14. Nbd2 
{White keeps developing.} Qb6 15. Rf1 {This retreat is only temporary.} Qc7 16. 
Nb3 b6 17. Re1 {Black has failed to obtain any counterplay and White has 
excellent control over the e5-square. It is now too risky for Black to play 
...f6 because White has increased his control over the center and Nxc5 would be 
an option (opening the position generally favors the side with the bishop 
pair).} Bb4 18. c3 Bc5 19. Rc1 Bb7 20. Nbd4 {[%cal Bg2g3,Bh2h4,Bc1c2,Bc2e2][%csl 
Ge5,Gd4] Black has nothing useful to do. White keeps strengthening his 
position.} Rae8 21. Rc2 Nf4 22. Bf1 Nf5 23. Bc1 {[%cal Gc1f4][%csl Rf4] Nxf5 
would double Black's pawns but White shouldn't give Black unnecessary activity.} 
Ng6 24. Bd3 Bc8 {“'Black may have been trying to prepare ...f6, but he never 
gets a suitable moment for it. Meanwhile White has been steadily improving his 
pieces, and he is now ready to seize more territory on the kingside.' - GM John 
Shaw”} 25. g3 {White prevents ...Nf4.} h6 26. h4 Qd8 27. h5 Nge7 28. Nb3 
{[%cal Bg3g4][%csl Rf5] “'Amazingly, Black's position is so congested that he 
has no defense against g3-g4 winning a piece!' - GM John Shaw”} Nxg3 29. Nxc5 
{[%cal Bf2g3][%csl Gc1,Gd3,Rg3]} Nxh5 30. Nh2 {[%cal Gd1h5][%csl Rh5]} bxc5 31. 
Qxh5 c4 32. Bf1 Nf5 33. Ba3 {[%cal Ga3f8][%csl Rf8]} d4 34. Bg2 {[%cal 
Bg2c6,Gc6e8][%csl Re8]} d3 35. Rd2 Ne7 36. Qg4 1-0

