{This game was played at the Alekhine Memorial in 2013 between Maxime 
Vachier-Lagrave (2722 FIDE) and Ding Liren (2707 FIDE).} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 
Bf5 4. h4 {[%cal Bg2g4][%csl Rf5] White gains kingside space and prevents Black 
from playing ...e6 due to g4 followed by h5 (trapping the bishop).} h6 {Black 
gives his bishop a retreat square on h7.} 5. g4 {White gains space with gain of 
tempo.} Be4 {Black provokes f3 before dropping his bishop back to h7.} (5... Bh7 
6. e6 {would be similar except White would be able to play} Nf3 {before f4.}) 6. 
f3 Bh7 7. e6 {[%csl Rf8] White sacrifices a pawn to obtain the e5-square and 
make it harder for Black to develop his dark-squared bishop.} Nf6 {“'This is 
quite a natural move, but it does not solve the problem with the e6-pawn 
blocking in the f8-bishop - something which goes on to haunt Black for the rest 
of the game.' - GM John Shaw”} 8. Bf4 {[%csl Ge5] White controls the 
e5-square. There is no need for White to capture on f7 because Black would be 
able to advance his e-pawn, preparing to develop his dark-squared bishop.} Qb6 
{[%cal Bb6b2][%csl Rb2] Black decides that normal development isn't good enough 
(Bf8 would be shut out of the game) so he decides to go pawn grabbing to get 
compensation.} 9. Nc3 {White should not defend his b2-pawn because that would be 
passive. White focuses on development instead.} Qxb2 10. Kd2 {[%cal Ba1b1][%csl 
Rb2,Rf8] White defends his c3-knight and c2-pawn. It doesn't matter that White 
is unable to castle, Black doesn't have enough development to punish White.} Qb6 
{Black retreats his queen before White plays Rb1.} (10... Bxc2 $2 11. Qxc2 Qxa1 
12. Bg2 {followed by Nge2 traps Black's queen.}) (10... Qa3 11. Qb1 {White has 
excellent compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) 11. Nge2 a6 {Too slow, but 
Black already had a tough position.} (11... fxe6 {intending a quick ...e5 was 
Black's best chance, but White would still have the advantage after} 12. Rb1 
{where Black has trouble developing.}) 12. Rb1 Qa7 13. Na4 {[%cal Ba4c5][%csl 
Gc5] White intends on playing Nc5.} b5 14. Nc5 Bg8 15. Be5 {White keeps 
improving his position and keeps the blockade. Black is unable to develop his 
dark-squared bishop.} fxe6 16. Nf4 {[%cal Bf4g6][%csl Gg6]} Nbd7 17. Nxd7 Nxd7 
18. Ng6 Nxe5 19. dxe5 {Black's kingside will never be able to develop. All that 
White needs to do to win is trade to an endgame where he can use his 'extra' 
pieces or start a queenside attack where Black doesn't have enough pieces to 
defend.} Rh7 20. h5 {White consolidates his g6-knight. Now ...Bh7-xg6 will never 
be a threat.} c5 21. f4 {[%csl Rf8,Rg8,Rh7,Ge5,Gh5,Gg6] White gains space.} Bf7 
22. Qf3 O-O-O 23. Be2 {Now that White has consolidated his kingside advantage 
and finished his development, he is now ready to start a queenside attack.} c4 
24. a4 {White wants to play axb5 to open the a-file.} Kc7 (24... Qb6 25. axb5 
axb5 {White can play} 26. Qa3 {or 26.Qe3 with a won position.}) 25. axb5 axb5 
26. Rxb5 Qd4+ {Black starts a counterattack, but it's easy to defend against his 
threats. Once White finishes defending, he will either trade queens with a won 
endgame or start an attack against Black's king.} 27. Ke1 Ra8 28. Rb1 Ra2 29. c3 
Qd2+ 30. Kf2 Rc2 31. Qe3 Qxe3+ {Otherwise White would have a decisive attack.} 
32. Kxe3 {White has a won endgame because it is impossible for Black to develop 
his kingside.} Rxc3+ 33. Kd4 Rc2 34. Rhe1 Kc6 35. Rb8 Bxg6 36. hxg6 Rh8 37. Reb1 
Rd2+ 38. Ke3 Ra2 39. R8b6+ Kc7 40. Kd4 {“'Ding Liren had enough. His 
incarcerated pieces will never get out.' - GM John Shaw”} 1-0

