{This game was part of the final section of the Candidates Tournament of 1974. 
Whoever won this 24 game match was supposed to play Bobby Fischer in the World 
Championships. Bobby Fischer defaulted, so this 24 game match decided the who 
was the World Champion.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. 
Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. h4 {White aims to pry open the 
h-file at the cost of a pawn.} Rc8 {Due to games like this which showed the ease 
in which White could get a powerful attack, masters who played the dragon began 
meeting h4 with ...h5, which became mainline.} 11. Bb3 Ne5 (11... h5 $1) 12. 
O-O-O (12. h5 $1 {is stronger, preventing} ...h5 {.}) Nc4 (12... h5 $1) 13. Bxc4 
Rxc4 14. h5 $1 {[%cal Bh5g6,Be3h6][%csl Rg6] Playing h4-h5 without g4 is usually 
more effective than g4 first because in these types of positions, attacking 
speed is very important (a delay can give Black more chances of generating 
queenside counterplay), and it is worth sacrificing a pawn to open the h file. 
If Black's attack was slowed by a tempo then g4 before h4 gives White a similar 
attack without losing a pawn.} Nxh5 {Taking with the pawn exposes Black's 
kingside too much.} 15. g4 Nf6 16. Nde2 {[%cal Be3h6,Gh1h7][%csl Rg8] 
Prophylaxis! White wants to bring his queen into the attack without allowing 
...Rxc3 (exposing White's queenside) so White defends against Black's only 
source of counterplay before continuing his attack.} Qa5 17. Bh6 Bxh6 18. Qxh6 
Rfc8 19. Rd3 {[%csl Gc3] Black has no counterplay due to White's defensive moves 
Nde2 and Rd3. Now White can finish Black off without having to calculate complex 
variations Where Black gets counterplay.} R4c5 $2 {Supposedly defending against 
White's threat of g5. But this is too slow - White can play it anyways. This is 
Black's only mistake this game} ({except for not playing the accurate 10...h5 or 
12...h5}) {but it was enough to lose.} (19... Qd8 {is stronger, but White still 
has a huge attack on the h file and can play} 20. g5 Nh5 21. Nf4 {White is 
significantly better but is probably not winning because in some lines Black can 
give back the pawn (and get a worse pawn structure) with} ...Qf8 {trading 
queens.}) 20. g5 $1 {[%cal Gh1h7,Bd3d5,Bc3d5][%csl Rf6,Rh7] Sacrificing a pawn.} 
Rxg5 (20... Nh5 21. Nf4 {Gives White a winning attack.}) 21. Rd5 Rxd5 22. Nxd5 
{Preparing to remove the defender of the h7 pawn with Nxf6+.} Re8 (22... Nxd5 
{fails to} 23. Qxh7+ Kf8 24. Qh8#) 23. Nef4 {[%cal Bd5f6,Bf4d5,Bh6h7][%csl 
Rf6,Rh7] Preparing to take on f6, take on h7 and play Nd5 (before or after Qh8+) 
cutting off the Black king's escape squares.} Bc6 24. e5 {Interference - 
preventing Black's queen from guarding the 5th rank.} Bxd5 (24... dxe5 25. Nxf6+ 
exf6 26. Nh5 {gives White a winning attack.}) 25. exf6 exf6 26. Qxh7+ Kf8 27. 
Qh8+ {Black resigns.} (27. Qh8+ 27... Ke7 28. Nxd5+ Qxd5 29. Re1+ {wins Black's 
rook or queen.}) 1-0

