{This game was played between World Champion Garry Kasparov and GM Boris Gelfand 
at the Linares tournament in 1993.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. 
Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 b5 ({...Nbd7 is an interesting alternative. Black delays 
his kingside development to play ...Nc5, attempting to trade off White's 
light-squared bishop. White should meet} 7... Nbd7 {with} 8. f4 {(intending 
f5).}) 8. O-O Be7 {Black prepares to castle.} 9. Qf3 {White develops his queen 
and threatens to play e5, attacking both Nf6 and Ra8.} Qc7 {Black prepares to 
meet e5 with ...Bb7.} (9... Qb6 {is an interesting alternative which should be 
met with 10.Be3 and will be covered in the theory chapter.}) 10. Qg3 {White 
threatens to play 11.Qxg7.} O-O {Black castles and defends against White's 
threat.} 11. Bh6 {[%cal Gg3g7,Gh6g7][%csl Rg7] White threatens Qxg7#. Black 
can't play ...gxh6 due to the pin.} Ne8 {Black guards the g7-square.} 12. Rad1 
{White finishes his development. Black can theoretically equalize, but White has 
the initiative due to his lead in development.} Bd7 {Black prepares to play 
...Nc6.} (12... Nc6 13. Nxc6 $1 Qxc6 14. Nd5 $1 {gives White a powerfully 
centralized knight.} 14... exd5 $2 {loses the exchange to} 15. Bxd5 {and 16. 
Bxa8.}) 13. Nf3 {[%cal Bc3e2,Be2f4][%csl Rg8] White brings his knight to the 
kingside to aid the attack.} b4 {13...Nc6 is the main move, though White can 
still fight for the initiative with 14.Bf4 followed by e5.} 14. Ne2 {White wants 
to attack on the kingside with all of his pieces. White's plan is to play 
Nf4-h5.} a5 {Black intends to trap White's bishop with ...a4.} 15. Nf4 {[%cal 
Bh6g7,Bf4h5][%csl Rg7] White allows Black to win his bishop. Black should not 
accept the sacrificed piece yet because White's kingside attack is becoming too 
dangerous to ignore.} Kh8 {Black unpins his g-pawn, threatening to play 
...gxh6.} (15... a4 {loses to} 16. Bxg7 Nxg7 17. Nh5) 16. Bg5 Nf6 17. Qh4 {[%cal 
Gh4e7,Bf4h5][%csl Re7] White adds pressure on the h4-d8 diagonal and prepares to 
play Nh5 (...Nxh5 can be met with Bxe7).} Bb5 {Black gains a tempo on Rf1 and 
prepares to defend his knight with ...Nbd7, finishing his development.} (17... 
a4 18. Bc4 $1 (18. Nh5 {also gives White a powerful initiative}) Qxc4 $2 19. e5 
$1 {White threatens both} exf6 {(winning a piece and opening the kingside) and 
Ng6+ (winning Black's queen due to the discovered attack).}) 18. Nd4 $1 {[%csl 
Re6] White fights for the initiative, sacrificing the exchange. White wants to 
sacrifice on e6 in order to open the position. Black must react, White is 
threatening both Nxb5 and the sacrifice on e6.} Be8 {Black guards the f7-square, 
preparing ...Bf7 in case White sacrifices on e6.} (18... Bxf1 19. Ndxe6 fxe6 20. 
Bxe6 {White is threatening Ng6#. Black can not defend against this threat 
without making significant concessions, so White has a decisive attack.}) (18... 
Bd7 {guards e6, but admits that ...Bb5 was a waste of time. White can continue 
the initiative with} 19. Rd3 {followed by} Rh3 {.}) 19. Ndxe6 $1 {White 
sacrifices to open the kingside. White is attacking with almost all of his 
pieces, while Black hasn't even finished his development.} fxe6 20. Nxe6 {White 
has a decisive attack.} Qa7 21. e5 {[%cal Gd1d8] White opens the d-file. He 
wants to have the option of Rd8 after he plays Nxf8.} dxe5 22. Nxf8 Bxf8 23. 
Bxf6 gxf6 24. Rd8 Nd7 25. Qg4 {Black resigns. White is threatening 26.Qg8# and 
25...Bg6 hangs the d7-knight.} 1-0

