[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4708283"]

{This game was played in 1996 between GM Alexei Shirov (once one of the top 10 
Grandmasters in the world) and GM Judit Polgar (the strongest woman chess 
player).} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 {White 
wants to develop his pieces rapidly and fight for a kingside initiative.} e6 7. 
O-O Be7 8. f4 {White gains space on the kingside and has the option of later 
playing e5.} O-O 9. Be3 {White finishes his development. He is ready to attack.} 
Qc7 {Black develops her queen.} (9... Nc6 {This move order (...Nc6 before 
...Qc7) makes} 10. g4 {less dangerous due to} 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 e5 {with an 
open center. This would not be possible without ...Nc6 because ...e5 could be 
met with Nf5. With} ...Nc6 {already played, White has a different powerful 
attacking plan: 10.Qe1 with Qg3 and Rae1. White is likely to play Bd3 and e5 to 
open the position. White has excellent center control and chances for a kingside 
attack.}) 10. g4 $1 {[%cal Bg4g5,Bf4f5][%csl Rf6] White is ready to pawn storm 
the kingside due to his lead in development and space advantage.} Re8 {Black 
prepares to play ...Bf8. Alternatives will be covered in the theory section.} 
11. f5 {White adds pressure on Black's e6-pawn and prepares to play g5.} (11. g5 
{is also good but after} 11... Nd7 12. f5 {Black has time to play} ...Ne5 {while 
if White played f5 before g5, Black would have trouble safely playing ...Nd7 due 
to the weakness of her e6-pawn.}) Bf8 {Black makes the most-natural move, the 
logical follow up to 10...Re8. However, 11...Bf8 allows White a combination 
which gives him a decisive attack. Alternatives will be covered in the theory 
section.} 12. g5 Nfd7 {[%cal Gf5e6,Gd4e6][%csl Re6]} 13. Nxe6 $1 {White 
sacrifices a piece to open the position.} fxe6 {White has a pawn (soon to be 2 
pawns) for the piece and a huge lead in development. Black's queenside is 
undeveloped and her kingside is exposed. For these reasons, White has more than 
enough compensation for the sacrificed piece.} 14. Bh5 {[%cal Gh5e8,Gf5e6][%csl 
Re8,Re6] White makes a useful in-between move before taking on e6.} g6 {Black 
sacrifices a pawn to be able to play ...Bg7 or ...Re7-g7.} (14... Re7 15. fxe6 
{White can rapidly bring all of his pieces into the attack (Bf7+, Nd5, Qf3).} 
15... Nb6 {This is a sample variation to prove that White is objectively 
winning.} 16. Qf3 {White threatens to play 17.Qxf8#.} 16... Qd8 17. Bxb6 Qxb6+ 
18. Rf2 Qd8 19. Raf1 {Black can not guard her f8-bishop.}) (14... Rd8 15. fxe6 
{White can rapidly bring all of his pieces into the attack (Bf7+, Nd5, Qh5 or 
Qf3).}) 15. fxg6 Re7 {Black can't take on g6 without accelerating White's 
attack.} (15... hxg6 16. Bxg6 Re7 17. Qh5 {White has a decisive attack can can 
follow up with Rf7.}) 16. Nd5 $1 {White sacrifices another piece to continue 
exposing Black's kingside.} exd5 {Black must accept the sacrifice or else he 
loses the exchange (Nxe7+) or allows Nf6+.} 17. Qxd5+ {[%csl 
Rg8,Gd5,Ge3,Gh5,Gf1]} Kh8 {Black's king is very weak and her queenside is still 
undeveloped. Black's extra 2 pieces do not matter because White has more than 2 
pieces extra in attacking power.} 18. gxh7 {White continues to open the kingside 
and threatens 20.Qg8#.} Rxh7 (18... Rg7 19. Bd4 {White wins the exchange because 
19... Ne5 loses to 20. Rxf8+.}) (18... Kxh7 19. g6+ Kh8 20. Bg4 {White will play 
Qh5+ next.}) 19. Bg6 {[%cal Bf1f7,Bf1f4,Bf4h4,Bg6h7,Be3d4][%csl Rh8]} (19. g6 
{also wins.}) Bg7 {Black sacrifices her rook to get some piece activity.} (19... 
Re7 {would lose to} 20. Rf4 {(Rf7 is also winning) with} Rh4+ {.}) 20. Bxh7 
{White accepts the sacrificed rook.} Qd8 (20... Kxh7 21. g6+ Kh8 22. Qh5+ Bh6 
23. Qxh6+ Kg8 24. Qh7#) 21. Bf5 {White has won his material back (he has a rook 
and 2 pawns for 2 minor pieces, which is approximately equal material) but still 
has a huge initiative due to Black's lack of queenside development and exposed 
kingside.} Ne5 22. Qd1 {White threatens to play Qh5+.} Bxf5 23. exf5 {[%cal 
Bf5f6,Bg5g6,Bd1h5][%csl Gf5,Gg5,Rh8] White now has 2 powerful connected passed 
pawns on the kingside.} Qe8 24. g6 {White easily wins with his initiative by 
attacking with all of his pieces and pawn storming Black's kingside.} Ng4 25. 
Bd4 Qe4 26. f6 Nc6 27. fxg7+ Kg8 28. Rf8+ Rxf8 29. gxf8=Q+ Kxf8 30. Qf1+ {Black 
resigns.} (30. Qf1+ 30... Ke8 31. Re1) (30. Qf1+ 30... Kg8 31. Qf7#) 1-0

[Event "Short & Sweet: Logozar's 1.e4 repertoire"]
[Site "Model games"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sicilian (Maroczy Bind): Sam Shankland"]
[Black "Gadir Guseinov"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SourceTitle "07 Model games"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-logozars-1e4-repertoire/course/27530, variation/4708284"]

{This game was played in the 2014 Qutar Masters tournament. White was rated 2642 
FIDE and Black was rated 2592 FIDE.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 ({The Maroczy bind can 
also be reached from 2...g6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Bg7 5.c4.}) 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 
{The Accelerated Dragon. Black fianchettos his dark-squared bishop. In 
comparison to the regular Dragon, Black delays the moves ...Nf6 and ...d6 in the 
hopes of playing ...d5 in one move. The downside of this approach is that White 
is able to play c4 before Nc3, with a bind on the d5-square, permanently ending 
Black's hopes of playing ...d5.} 5. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4] White gains space and 
increases his control over the d5-square before playing Nc3.} Bg7 6. Be3 {[%cal 
Bb1c3,Bf1e2,Be1g1,Bh1f1]} Nf6 7. Nc3 {White harmoniously develops his pieces 
toward the center.} O-O (7... Ng4 8. Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 {Black has successfully 
traded a pair of minor pieces, but White still has more space and easier 
development.}) 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Bd7 (9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bd7 11. Qd3 $1 {White 
doesn't need to play} f3 {to support his center, he can play f4 instead. Qd2 is 
usually more ideal than Qd3 with Black's queenside knight on c6, as Black would 
be able to meet Qd3 with ...Ne5, but without the possibility of ...Ne5, Qd3 is 
more logical.}) 10. Nc2 {[%cal Bd1d2,Bf1d1,Ba1c1,Bf2f3,Bf3f4][%csl Gc4,Ge4] 
Trading pieces would help Black get some breathing room, as White has more 
space. White prevents ...Nxd4 (trading pieces and preparing ...Bc6). Black now 
has a very cramped position.} Qa5 {Black develops his queen to an active square. 
Alternatives will be covered in the theory section.} 11. f4 {[%cal 
Bb2b4,Ba2a3,Bd1d2][%csl Ge5,Ra5] White gains kingside space and prevents ...Qe5. 
Since Black doesn't have any good squares for his queen on the 5th rank, White 
is able to target it with a3 (or Rb1) and b4.} Rac8 12. Rc1 {White develops his 
rook, moving it off of Bg7's x-ray. It is often a good idea to prepare b4 (or 
b3) by developing White's queenside rook to avoid any tactics involving a 
discovered attack from Black's dark-squared bishop.} (12. Rb1 {is also strong.}) 
Be6 {Black targets White's c4-pawn. There isn't much else that he can do.} 13. 
a3 {White prepares to play b4.} Nb8 {[%cal Gc8c4,Ge6c4][%csl Rc4] Black moves 
his knight off of the open c-file in order to target White's c4-pawn.} 14. Nd5 
{[%cal Bd5e7][%csl Re7] White centralizes his knight and interferes with Be6's 
attack on the c4-pawn. White is okay with Black exchanging on d5 because when 
White recaptures, he will increase his space advantage.} Rfe8 {Black protects 
his e7-pawn.} (14... Nxe4 15. Nxe7+) (14... Nxd5 15. exd5) 15. Qd3 {[%csl Ge4] 
White finishes his development and protects his e4-pawn.} (15. b4 {is also 
strong.}) ({The pawn sacrifice} 15. Nd4 {, impeding} ...b5 {, is also strong.} 
15... Nxe4 {The only possible punishment. 16. Nxe6 fxe6} 17. Bg4 {White has more 
than enough compensation for his sacrificed pawn.}) Nbd7 (15... Nxd5 16. exd5) 
(15... b5 16. cxb5) 16. b4 Qa6 17. Nd4 {[%cal Bh2h3,Bg2g4,Bd4b5][%csl 
Gb4,Gc4,Ge4,Gf4,Rc7] White's space advantage and superior center control gives 
him domination over the board. Black has no good plan and White is ready to 
begin aggressive action. From the objective point of view, White's positional 
advantage is decisive.} Bxd5 {Black couldn't avoid exchanging on d5 forever, Nd5 
applied too much pressure on Black's position to ignore.} (17... Bg4 18. Bxg4 
Nxg4 19. Nb5) 18. exd5 {[%csl Re7,Ge3,Ge2] Other than White's space advantage 
and superior piece activity, now White also has the bishop pair and can pressure 
Black's backward e7-pawn.} b6 19. Bf3 Qb7 20. Rfe1 Nb8 21. Bf2 {[%cal 
Ge1e7,Bc1c2,Bc2e2,Bf4f5][%csl Re7] White's bishops no longer interfere with 
White's pressure down the e-file.} Qd7 22. h3 {No counterplay allowed! Not even 
something as harmless as ...Ng4 should be allowed.} ({The aggressive} 22. f5 {is 
also powerful.}) e5 {Black opens the center. This favors White because of his 
superior piece activity and bishop pair. Another downside of ...e5 is that White 
can apply pressure against Black's d6-pawn. If Black continued to wait, White 
would have doubled rooks on the e-file with pressure against Black's e7-pawn and 
opened the kingside with f5.} 23. dxe6 fxe6 24. Nb5 {[%cal 
Gd3d6,Gb5d6,Bc1d1][%csl Rd6] White targets Black's d6-pawn.} d5 {Black strikes 
in the center. If Black did not play ...d5, this d6-pawn would eventually fall.} 
(24... Rcd8 25. Rcd1) 25. cxd5 Rxc1 (25... Nxd5 26. Bxd5) (25... exd5 26. Rxe8+) 
26. Rxc1 Nxd5 27. Bxd5 {[%cal Bc1c7][%csl Ra7,Rd7] White forces Black to create 
a weakness; his d5-pawn will be isolated.} Qxd5 (27... exd5 28. Rc7) 28. Qxd5 
{Though White could keep the queens on the board, it makes sense to trade 
because the endgame is winning for White.} exd5 29. Nxa7 {[%cal Bf2b6][%csl 
Gb4,Ga3,Rb6,Rd5] White is now ahead a pawn with superior piece activity. Black 
also has 2 isolated pawns: b6 and d5. The rest is a matter of technique.} Bb2 
30. Rb1 {[%cal Bb1b2,Gb2a3,Ga7b5][%csl Rb2]} Re2 (30... Bxa3 31. Nb5) 31. Nb5 
Nc6 32. Bxb6 {[%csl Ga3,Gb4] White has 2 extra pawns.} Kf7 33. Rd1 {[%cal 
Bd1d5][%csl Rd5]} Ne7 34. a4 {[%cal Ba4a5,Ba5a6,Ba6a7,Ba7a8] White has 2 
connected passed pawns on the queenside. As long as White doesn't allow too much 
counterplay, White should easily win by advancing them.} Nc6 35. Bc5 d4 36. a5 
Bc3 37. Nxc3 dxc3 38. Rc1 1-0

